  NULL,
  'Stable, Data Deficient',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 9 - 11; Dorsal soft rays: 22-24; Anal spines: 4; Anal soft rays: 20 - 23.", "appearance": "It has microscopic, sharp scales that run around the highly compressed round flat body. Its body is so thin it can hardly be seen from the front. Its large eyes are near the top of its head and provide it with the binocular vision and depth perception it needs to catch prey. The fish is an olive-green colour with a silver white belly with a large dark spot, surrounded by a light ring on each side of the body.", "about": "This benthopelagic coastal fish species is widely distributed in the Atlantic, Pacific and Indian Ocean, and along the entire West African coast, Southeast Asia, New Zealand, Australia, the coasts of Japan, and on the coasts of Europe. They live near the seabed, living in depths from 5 to 360 m. Abundance is greatest in shallow warmer waters.  They are normally solitary. It primarily eats smaller fish, especially schooling fish such as sardines. Occasionally it eats squid and cuttlefish. It is delicious to eat.", "biology": "When John Dories are 3 or 4 years of age, they are ready to reproduce. This happens around the end of winter. They are substrate scatterers; they release sperm and eggs into the water to fertilize. Typical lifespan is about 12 years in the wild. The maximum size for this species is 90 cm and 8 kg; Common length: 40.0 cm TL. The maximum reported age for this species is 12 years.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
  '[{"measure": "TL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.0224, "exponent": 2.9, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

