  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Southern Driftfish", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 10-13; Dorsal soft rays: 14-16; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 13-15.", "appearance": "It is silvery with a purple tinge. Fins are grayish.", "about": "The Indian Driftfish is found in the Indo-Pacific from South Africa to the Persian Gulf and east to the Indo-Malayan region up to Fiji, and north to Japan at a depth range of 20-300 m. It occurs in small schools in areas with muddy substrates on the continental shelf and upper slope and feeds mainly on zooplankton. It appears to be pelagic at night and demersal by day and may migrate seasonally.", "biology": "The Indian Driftfish is oviparous (egg laying), gonochorous (separate sexes), with pelagic eggs. Maturity is attained at ~15.1 cm. Max length: 25.0 cm SL (male); Common length: 18.0 cm SL (male).", "citation": "FishBase"}',
