  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  'Depleted',
  '{"other_names": "Blackedged Conger", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 0; Anal spines: 0; Vertebrae: 139-146.", "appearance": "Flanges on upper and lower lips are well developed; 2 rows of teeth in jaws, those of outer row larger; closely set and compressed to form cutting edge. Dorsal fin begins over middle of appressed pectoral fin. Colouration: Brownish grey, yellow below and on fins, median fins with narrow black edge, black patch on lower rear edge of eye and on pectorals; assumes a pattern of broad dark bands at night.", "about": "This species is widespread throughout the Indian and Pacific oceans occurring in tropical, marine and brackish waters on coral reefs, generally on ledges and in crevices, shallow lagoons, slopes, and reef flats, to 80 m depth. It is also occasionally found in estuaries. They are generally known to only emerge into the open at night to feed on small fishes and invertebrates. It is generally a solitary species.", "biology": "Length at maturity is unknown. Maximum TL for this species is 140 cm (male); Common TL for this species is 50.0 cm (male).", "citation": "FishBase"}',
