  '{"other_names": "Cape Conger", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 0; Anal spines: 0; Vertebrae: 140-142.", "appearance": "It is brownish grey dorsally and creamy white ventrally with a wide dusky margin on median fins.", "about": "This species is found in the southwestern Pacific and the Indian Ocean from Australia and New Zealand to the Cape of Good Hope, South Africa to southern Mozambique and east to east to Kermadec Islands and Tuvalu. It inhabits estuaries, rocky and coral reefs down to 30 m. It takes refuge in structure during most of the day and emerges to feed at night upon crustaceans and small fishes. It has also been reported to consume fish, crustaceans, shellfish, octopus, squid, crabs, and seaweed. Its flesh is highly esteemed.", "biology": "Max length: 150 cm TL (male).", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
