  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Bony, Orangemouth Anchovy", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 0; Dorsal soft rays: 13-14; Anal spines: 0; Anal soft rays: 34-44.", "appearance": "A dark blotch appears behind upper part of gill opening. The inside of the gill cavity is bright orange.", "about": "Found in the Indian Ocean: Madagascar; coasts of Africa from Port Alfred to lower Zambezi delta in Mozambique and northward to the Persian Gulf, coasts of Pakistan and India. It is a coastal, pelagic species, apparently common along shore and in estuaries. Presumably schooling, occurring inshore and entering estuaries and lagoons, perhaps used as nursery areas, but moving further out in rainy seasons when coastal waters are freshened up by rivers and are less saline. It feeds on plankton organisms. This species is an important targeted resource in beach seine fisheries of Mozambique, where the abundance has declined.", "biology": "Max length: 22.0 cm TL. The life span is about 3 years.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
