  'Stable, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 8; Dorsal soft rays: 9; Anal spines: 1; Anal soft rays: 7.", "appearance": "Back grey to olive, sides and belly whitish; 1-2 longitudinal yellow bands; dark blotch below 1st dorsal fin. Yellow-mid-lateral stripe from eye to tail and some yellow striping on cheek and along abdomen.", "about": "This species is widespread and relatively common throughout the Indo-West Pacific: Persian Gulf; Red Sea and East Africa to the Hawaiian, Marquesan, and Ducie islands, north to the Ryukyu and Bonin Islands, south to Lord Howe and Rapa Islands. This species is found over sandy bottoms in calm lagoons or bays in shallow, coastal waters. Young are often observed in schools. During the hot seasons in the Persian Gulf, this species is seen in coastal lagoons. During the day, it is often seen in semi-stationary aggregations on reefs. At night, individuals feed over open bottoms. This species diet consists of a variety of small invertebrates, including crabs, shrimps, polychaetes, spunculids, small pelecypods and gastropods, hermit crabs, heart urchin and planktonic animals. It also occasionally captures small fishes.", "biology": "Estimated mean length at first sexual maturity: 16 cm.  Males mature as small as 12.3 cm SL and females as small as 11.2 cm SL; spawning takes place from December to September with peaks in March and April.  Large schools of silvery postlarvae settle on reef flats in March to June at a standard length of 6-8 cm. Spawning takes place over sandy areas near reef''s edge for several days following the new moon. Max length: 43.0 cm TL; Common length: 25.0 cm TL; Max. published weight: 423.3 g.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Glossogobius giuris',
  'Tank Goby',
  'Tenk Dikkop',
  'Goby Tank',
  ARRAY['Sompat Grunt'],
  'Gobiidae',
  'Gobies',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 7; Dorsal soft rays: 8-9; Anal spines: 1; Anal soft rays: 8 - 9.", "appearance": "The head is flattened with a protruding lower jaw while the body takes on a compressed appearance towards to caudal fin. The body is pale brownish yellow with 5 to 6 dark and rounded spots on its sides. Some specimens living on dark substrates can be very dark also without longitudinal lines. Dorsal fins with small spots forming longitudinal stripes. Pelvic fins jointed but attached to the body only from their anterior part. Some livings on very light substrates show an ivory colouration. Dorsal fins are light with brownish spots. Pelvic fins are grey. Pectorals and caudal fins are grey and often glassy and translucent.", "about": "The Tank Goby a subtropical species native to fresh, marine and brackish waters from the Red Sea and East Africa through South Asia and the Indian Ocean to China, Australia and the islands of the Pacific Ocean. It is most often associated with estuarine habitats, although it is also found in marine water and can be found many kilometers inland in freshwater streams, up to 300 km inland in Malawi. This species is a benthopelagic and amphidromous goby which is found in clear to turbid streams with rock, gravel, or sandy substrates. They grow to a much larger size in brackish water than in fresh water. It is a carnivorous fish and will eat any small fish and invertebrates it comes across. Cannibalism has been recorded. Like most gobies, it stays on the bottom and rarely rises into the water column.", "biology": "It lays eggs amongst submerged vegetation, where the eggs are guarded by both the male and the female. They will spawn in freshwater, the eggs being taken to the sea by the current, although it can complete its whole life cycle in fresh water. In South Africa it breeds in the summer. Max length: 50.0 cm SL; Common length: 11.3 cm SL.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  '[{"measure": "TL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.011, "exponent": 3.0, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Pomadasys jubelini',
  'Atlantic Spotted Grunter',
  'Atlantiese Gespikkelde Knorder',
  'Grunter Atlantic Spotted',
  NULL,
  'Haemulidae',
  'Grunts',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Sompat Grunt", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 11-12; Dorsal soft rays: 15-17; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 8-9.", "appearance": "The body is oblong and compressed. The snout is short and pointed. A deep groove and a pore exist above maxilla, below the preorbital bone. Last dorsal spine is longer than penultimate one. The second anal fin spine is longer and stouter than third and the third anal spine may also be thick but always shorte. Caudal fin slightly forked; Colouration: silvery, with round, dark brown or black and irregularly scattered spots following scale rows on back and sides. Small-sized specimens <60 mm SL may lack spots, from this size on spots gradually become visible and pattern is well-developed in specimens of about 100 mm SL or larger; no spot on the snout. Black opercular spot present at angle of opercle. Dorsal and caudal fins are grey.", "about": "It is distributed in the Eastern Atlantic: west coast of Africa, from Mauritania to southern Angola. It inhabits sandy and muddy bottoms of coastal waters and estuaries and sometimes found in freshwater. It is a bottom-living, but periodically pelagic, species usually inhabiting littoral waters to about 25 m depth, but has been reported to extend down to about 90 m. It feeds on fish and benthic crustaceans as well as on mollusks and worms. Of all grunts found in the continental waters of Lower Guinea, this species is found farthest upstream and seems best adapted to freshwater environments.", "biology": "It breeds in brackish water lagoons and estuaries, and even freshwaters. In Nigeria, it spawns between July and September. Maturity occurs at about 13.1 cm. Max length: 60.0 cm TL; Common length: 45.0 cm TL.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Pomadasys multimaculatus',
  'Cock Grunter',
  'Haan Knorder',
  'Grunter Cock',
  NULL,
  'Haemulidae',
  'Grunts',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 12; Dorsal soft rays: 13; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 7.", "appearance": "Silvery, darker above; head and body covered with dark spots.", "about": "The Cock Grunter is demersal and distributed in the Indian Ocean: east coast of Africa to Australia and is found in marine, brackish waters with a depth range of 20-50 m. It inhabits coastal waters and is plentiful in tidal estuaries. It is not eaten around the Island of Mozambique because the natives believe it is responsible for leprosy; others consider the flesh causes boils. It is an excellent food fish.", "biology": "Max length: 76.0 cm TL; Common length: 60.0 cm TL.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
  '[{"measure": "TL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.0347, "exponent": 2.83, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Pomadasys furcatus',
  'Grey Grunter',
  'Grys Knorder',
  'Grunter Grey',
  ARRAY['Banded Grunter'],
  'Haemulidae',
  'Grunts',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": " Banded Grunter", "meristics": "Dorsal spines; 12; Dorsal soft rays: 14-15; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 7.", "appearance": "This is a small, deep-bodied grunter with a steep head profile and a short snout. Overall colour is silvery grey with horizontal brown stripes along the upper body.", "about": "Grey Grunters are distributed in the indo-Pacific including the east coast of Africa, Madagascar, Red Sea and Indonesia. In southern Africa they are found mainly along the Maputaland coast and rare south of Durban. A tag-recapture study conducted in the St Lucia Marine Reserve has shown that this species is highly resident with a mean distance moved of only 138 m from 55 recaptures. Adults inhabit shallow inshore reefs and sandy areas close to reefs, mainly in the surf zone. Little is known regarding the juvenile habitat but is thought to be similar to adults.  Adults eat small crabs, shrimps, mole crabs and polychaete worms but the diet of juveniles is unknown. They are a small fish species commonly caught by subsistence and recreational shore fishers along the KZN north coast. Grey Grunter comprised only 0.14% of fish kept by shore anglers sampled along the KZN coast, although this survey did not cover the Maputaland area north of Cape Vidal thoroughly. In the St Lucia Marine Reserve north of Cape Vidal Grey Grunter comprised 21% by number of shore anglers\u2019 catches in a research fishing project from 2001-2011. Catch composition showed a slight increase, and a significant increase in mean size (250-270 mm FL), in the previously exploited area between Cape Vidal and Leven Point over this 10 year period following the implementation of the beach vehicle ban in Jan 2002. This resident species is abundant in the St Lucia and Maputaland MPAs and receives protection within the no-take sanctuary areas within these reserves.", "biology": "The Grey Grunter\u2019s reproductive style is unknown but probably gonochoristic (separate sexes). Ripe fish have been encountered in spring in northern KZN, and their breeding/spawning locality is little known, probably limited to the inshore waters of the Maputaland coast. Their age at maturity is unknown but their length at sexual maturity is recorded to be attained at ~20 cm TL. The maximum recorded age is unknown. The maximum recorded weight is 1 kg, and the maximum recorded length is 50 cm TL but few exceed 40 cm TL.", "citation": "BQ Mann, SW Dunlop In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, FishBase, ORI Fish Fact Sheet"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.03, "exponent": 2.84, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Pomadasys kaakan',
  'Javelin Grunter',
  'Spies Knorder',
  'Grunter Javelin',
  ARRAY['Moff Grunter'],
  'Haemulidae',
  'Grunts',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Not Evaluated',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Moff Grunter", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 12; Dorsal soft rays: 13-15; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 7.", "appearance": "This species is distinguished by the following characters: chin with 2 pores with a median pit; head blunt, its upper profile convex; mouth small; maxilla reaching to eye; teeth in jaws arranged in villiform (brushlike) bands; Colour: juveniles brilliant silvery green above to golden silver on sides and silvery white on belly with 12 or more faint vertical bars comprised of small dark brown spots or irregular blotches; dorsal fin spotted with black-brown spots on lower half of spinous dorsal fin and in 3 rows on rayed dorsal fin; margin of soft dorsal fin darker and lower tip of caudal fin milk white; adults uniform golden green above, silvery below with traces of the vertical bars present only when alive and spots on dorsal fins indistinct or absent.", "about": "The global distribution of Javelin Grunters is in tropical and subtropical Indo-West Pacific, from the Red Sea south to at least the Mbashe Estuary in the former Transkei in the EC.  Adults are found in soft substrata in estuaries and shallow coastal waters to 75 m depth; often associated with wrecks. Juveniles utilise estuaries as nursery areas. The adults feed on crabs and polychaetes (bristle worms) while the juveniles on copepods (small aquatic crustaceans). They are seldom seen in KZN and Transkei shore angling catches. Also, not very common in KZN estuarine angling catches except quite commonly caught by boat anglers in Richards Bay harbor. Quite common in historical and more recent (illegal) gill net catches from Mhlatuze Estuary. Not commonly caught from KZN offshore skiboats and not reported in spearfishing catches. Large fish fairly commonly caught and retained by shallow water prawn trawlers on the Thukela Bank although effort in this fishery is currently extremely low.", "biology": "The Javelin Grunter\u2019s reproductive style is unknown but likely to be gonochoristic (separate sexes). The breeding/spawning season occurs during winter in KZN reportedly near river mouths and ripe and spent fish have been reported from the Thukela Banks. Their age at maturity is unknown but their length at sexual maturity is 35 cm TL (Asia-Pacific). The maximum recorded age is unknown. The maximum recorded weight is 5,7 kg and the maximum recorded length is 80 cm TL.", "citation": "ST Fennessy, BQ Mann In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, FishBase"}',
  '[{"measure": "TL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.01445, "exponent": 2.98, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Pomadasys olivaceus',
  'Olive Grunter',
  'Olyf Knorder',
  'Grunter Olive',
  ARRAY['Pinky','Piggy','Varkie'],
  'Haemulidae',
  'Grunts',
  7.5,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  'Optimally exploited, 40-50% of pristine',
  '{"other_names": "Pinky, Piggy, Varkie", "appearance": "Dorsal spines: 12; Dorsal soft rays: 15-17; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 11-13. Olive Grunter are silver to greenish, darker above; dark blotch on upper opercle; young with yellowish fins, older specimens dusky.", "about": "Their distribution is widespread in the Indian Ocean; found off India, Arabia, Madagascar and extending along the entire east African coast extending to False Bay in the WC. They are resident with no long shore migration known. There is however a trend in size with depth with adult fish found in deeper water in the EC. Similarly, in KZN adult fish migrate offshore into slightly deeper water to spawn. Adults are found on offshore reefs or soft substrate banks from 10-90 m, often aggregating around pinnacles and shipwrecks. Juveniles inhabit inshore surf-zone reefs down to 10 m, sandy beach surf zone and the lower reaches of estuaries. The adult diet consists primarily of crustaceans including shrimps and shrimp-like crustaceans, and polychaete worms while the juveniles eat small crustaceans and polychaetes (bristle worms). Olive Grunter are an important shore angling species in KZN and the EC, often caught by subsistence fishers or used as bait by recreational anglers. They are caught as a bycatch in the prawn trawl fishery on the shallow Thukela Banks and inshore trawls in the southern Cape and in the beach seine net fishery in Durban Bay. Occasionally they are caught for bait by recreational ski-boat anglers.  Olive Grunter are an extremely abundant species throughout their distribution and form an important prey species for larger fish.", "biology": "Their reproductive style is unknown, probably gonochoristic (separate sexes). The breeding/spawning season is prolonged, occurring throughout the year in KZN and EC with a slight peak in winter in water 10-30 m depth probably along most of the east coast of SA although not common north of Cape Vidal. Their age at maturity for combined sexes is 3 years in KZN with a length at maturity of combined sexes is 130 mm FL. The maximum recorded age is 10 years. The maximum recorded weight is 0,4 kg and the maximum recorded length is 31 cm TL.", "citation": "BQ Mann, SW Dunlop In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, FishBase"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.0452, "exponent": 2.69, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Pomadasys maculatus',
  'Saddle Grunter',
  'Saal Knorder',
  'Grunter Saddle',
  NULL,
  'Haemulidae',
  'Grunts',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 12; Dorsal soft rays: 13-14; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 7.", "appearance": "It is a small-sized fish of moderately deep body. Isthmus narrow, forming a groove. Chin with 2 pairs or small pores. This species is characterized by several dark large elongate blotches on the upper back, one forming a saddle on the nape.", "about": "The Saddle Grunter is distributed in the Indo-West Pacific: throughout the Indian Ocean and the western Pacific, north to China, south to Australia. It is an amphidromous species (fishes that regularly migrate between freshwater and the sea in both directions) that is found in coastal inshore waters at a depth range of 20-110 m. It inhabits sandy bottoms close to reefs, open bays, trawling grounds, and estuaries.  It feeds on crustaceans and fish. It is eible but spoils easily.", "biology": "It is oviparous (egg laying) with distinct pairing during breeding. Max length: 59.3 cm TL; Common length: 30.0 cm TL; Max. published weight: 3.2 kg.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "BRINCA, L. et al.", "formula_type": "log-linear", "coefficient": -10.75699043, "exponent": 2.899035931}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Pomadasys commersonnii',
  'Spotted Grunter',
  'Gespikkelde Knorder',
  'Grunter Spotted',
  ARRAY['Spotty','Tiger','Knorhaan','Spikkel Knorder','Inkolokolo'],
  'Haemulidae',
  'Grunts',
  40,
  NULL,
  5,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Not Evaluated',
  'Collapsed,  <24% of pristine',
  '{"other_names": "Spotty, Tiger, Knorhaan, Inkolokolo", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 10 - 11; Dorsal soft rays: 14-15; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 9-10.", "appearance": "It is one of the largest grunters with a distinctive, long, sloping forehead and a body that narrows towards the tail. Overall colour is silvery grey with numerous small black spots on the sides. The spots do not extend onto the head. Juveniles are without spots on the body.", "about": "Spotted Grunter are distributed in the tropical and warm temperate western Indian Ocean from India to False Bay. In southern Africa they are found along the entire eastern seaboard of SA. No population differentiation is observed between genetic samples from the EC to KZN, indicating that the different regions along the SA coast are highly connected. They are considered resident but despite making seaward migrations to spawn, Spotted Grunters are largely resident to one estuary. ORI tagging data revealed that 95% of recaptures were made within 3.5km of the release site and only 2% moved more than 100km. Acoustic telemetry studies have confirmed extreme residency by juveniles in both permanently open and intermittently open estuaries. Extreme weather events (with sharp barometric pressure drops) can displace resident individuals from their home estuaries.  Adults inhabit estuaries and coastal waters over soft sediments. Adults also venture into the river/estuary interface (freshwater), presumably to get rid of parasites. Juveniles can be found in estuaries, harbours, coastal embayments and shallow coastal waters. Spotted Grunter, which were rare in the Southwestern Cape are now commonly caught in this cool-temperate bioregion probably due to climate change. The adult estuarine fish\u2019s diet of consists of crustaceans and molluscs (e.g. sand prawn, mud prawn, pencil bait and the relative importance of the dominant prey varies between estuaries. In the Great Fish Estuary juveniles (< 300 mm TL) mostly consumed the endemic amphipod Grandidierella lignorum (63%) but also sand prawn (31%). In Durban harbor the diet included bivalve siphon tips, benthic crustaceans and polychaetes (bristle worms). Spotted Grunter are a very important recreational angling species in estuaries throughout its distribution from the Breede Estuary to Kosi Bay. Also, an important species in estuarine-based subsistence fisheries and illegal gill net and trap fisheries however less important in the coastal shore fishery and skiboat fishery. They are occasionally taken in the recreational spearfishery and as a bycatch of inshore trawlers on the Thukela Banks. The Stilbaai, Dwesa-Cwebe and Pondoland MPAs include no-take EPAs that benefit this species. The no-take wilderness areas in the Richards Bay, St Lucia and Kosi Bay estuarine systems are also likely to provide some protection for juveniles.", "biology": "Spotted Grunter are gonochoristic (separate sexes). Their breeding/spawning season is Aug-Dec in KZN in coastal waters adjacent to estuary mouths and in harbours. Spawning is not recorded in EC. Ripe running individuals have been recently reported from the Breede Estuary during summer. Males mature at 2.5 years and at 330 mm TL while females mature at 3 years at 390 mm TL in KZN. There are reports of males maturing at 3 years in the EC, while another report calculated 3.2 years for combined sexes. The maximum recorded age varies with estimates ranging from 14-15 years in the EC and between 15-19 years in KZN. The maximum recorded weight: 9.5 kg (Durban KZN; 1949). The maximum recorded length: 910 mm FL.", "citation": "PD Cowley, ST Fennessy In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, FishBase, ORI Fish Fact Sheet"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 3e-05, "exponent": 2.885, "formula_type": "power-mm", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Pomadasys striatus',
  'Striped Grunter',
  'Gestreepte Knorder',
  'Grunter Striped',
  NULL,
  'Haemulidae',
  'Grunts',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 12; Dorsal soft rays: 13-14; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 6-7.", "appearance": "Some specimens are dark brown, with barely visible dark longitudinal stripes.", "about": "This species has a relatively small distribution off southern East Africa known originally from Beira, Mozambique to Knysna, South Africa. It inhabits nearshore reef habitats and can be common and locally abundant. This species inhabits quiet bays and protected rocky and coral reefs down to 30 m. It forms small shoals over sandy bottom with scattered reefs where it feeds on small crustaceans. It is not found in estuaries and is probably intolerant of turbid water and low salinity. This species is used for bait because it is usually too small to be of importance as a food fish.", "biology": "Max length: 22.0 cm TL.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
  '[{"measure": "TL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.02042, "exponent": 3.0, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Acroteriobatus blochii',
  'Bluntnose Guitarfish',
  'Stompneus Sandkruiper',
  'Guitarfish Bluntnose',
  ARRAY['Bluntnose Fiddlefish'],
  'Rhinobatidae',
  'Guitarfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  1,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Stable, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Bluntnose Fiddlefish", "appearance": "This guitarfish has a broadly pointed snout and a broad pectoral disc. It is plain brown above, young with white spots.", "about": "The Bluntnose Guitarfish occurs in the Southeast Atlantic from southern Angola to Cape Town, South Africa. Restricted range, apparent rarity, unknown population size, and occurrence in relatively shallow depths make the Bluntnose Guitarfish potentially susceptible to fishing activities. In South Africa, this species is caught in gillnet, beach seine, commercial and recreational line fisheries. Some beach seine fishers have reported substantial landings of guitarfish (up to 10 t per year, likely also including both the Bluntnose Guitarfish and Lesser Guitarfish, due to identification issues). Recreational fishers along the Namibia coast catch this species but they are not targeted nor are they used, with most individuals being released alive. This species is, however, subject to high levels of post-release mortality, especially in some cases where fishers leave them on the beach to die. Catch records from local fisheries should continue to be monitored.", "biology": "It is ovoviviparous (internal fertilization and the young are born alive) with embryos feeding initially on yolk, then receiving additional nourishment from the mother by indirect absorption of uterine fluid enriched with mucus, fat or protein through specialised structures do not feed off the mother. The young are born as miniature adults, free-swimming and feeding. Max length: 100.0 cm TL.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
  '[{"measure": "TL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.00316, "exponent": 3.11, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Rhina ancylostomus',
  'Bowmouth Guitarfish',
  'Boogbek Sandkruiper',
  'Guitarfish Bowmouth',
  NULL,
  'Rhinobatidae',
  'Guitarfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  1,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Decreasing, Critically Endangered',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "appearance": "The Bowmouth Guitarfish is an unmistakable guitarfish with a broad, rounded snout, large, high pectoral fins, and heavy ridges of spiky thorns over the eyes and on the back and shoulders; jaws with heavily ridged, crushing teeth in undulating rows. Its mouth forms a W-shaped undulating line. The body is deepest in front of the two tall and falcate (sickle-shaped) dorsal fins.  The broad and triangular pectoral fins have a deep indentation where their leading margins meet the head. The pelvic fins are much smaller than the pectoral fins, and the anal fin is absent. The tail is much longer than the body and ends in a large, crescent-shaped caudal fin; the lower caudal fin lobe is more than half the length of the upper. The entire dorsal surface has a grainy texture from a dense covering of tiny dermal denticles. A thick ridge is present along the midline of the back, which bears a band of sharp, robust thorns. There is also a pair of thorn-bearing ridges in front of the eyes, a second pair running from above the eyes to behind the spiracles, and a third pair on the \"shoulders\". This species is bluish to brownish gray above, lightening towards the margins of the head and over the pectoral fins. There are prominent white spots scattered over the body and fins, a white-edged black marking above each pectoral fin, and two dark transverse bands atop the head between the eyes. The underside is light gray to white. Young rays are more vividly coloured than adults, which are browner with fainter patterning and proportionately smaller spots.", "about": "This rare species occurs widely in the tropical coastal waters of the western Indo-Pacific, from KwaZulu-Natal in South Africa to the Red Sea (including the Seychelles), across the Indian subcontinent and Southeast Asia (including the Maldives), to Shark Bay in Western Australia at depths of up to 90 m. This guitarfish spends most of its time near the sea floor but can occasionally be seen swimming in midwater. It favors sandy or muddy habitats, and can also be found in the vicinity of rocky and coral reefs and shipwrecks. It is a strong swimmer that propels itself with its tail like a shark. It is more active at night and is not known to be territorial. This species feeds mainly on demersal bony fishes such as croakers and crustaceans such as crabs and shrimp; bivalves and cephalopods are also consumed. Its bands of flattened teeth allow it to crush hard-shelled prey.", "biology": "Length at maturity: 150 - 178 cm. Max length: 300 cm TL. Max. published weight: 135.0 kg.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  '[{"measure": "TL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.00389, "exponent": 3.12, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Rhynchobatus djiddensis',
  'Giant Guitarfish',
  'Reus Sandkruiper',
  'Guitarfish Giant',
  ARRAY['Giant Sandshark','Whitespotted Wedgefish'],
  'Rhinobatidae',
  'Guitarfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  1,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Decreasing, Critically Endangered',
  'Critically Endangered',
  '{"other_names": " Giant Sandshark, Whitespotted Wedgefish", "appearance": "The Giant Guitarfish is a large guitarfish with large black eyespots on the pectoral bases, a distinctive black cross between the eyes, and rows of small white spots on the upper body; snout pointed and lower caudal lobe short. Their tails have a typical shark-like shape, but their heads are guitar-like in shape unlike the disc-shape found in rays. They are olive-green above, white below. Mouths are small and contain flattened, pavement-like teeth.", "about": "Giant Guitarfish are restricted to the Red Sea and tropical waters of the WIO south to SA. They are commonly found in KZN and the Pondoland area of the EC during summer, known to occur as far south as Knysna but seldom found south of Port St Johns. They are considered nomadic. Based on tagging data and shore anglers\u2019 catches, adults of this species appear to be fairly mobile. Although movement patterns are difficult to interpret, it is likely that they will move southwards down the coast during the summer months and return to northern KZN and MOZ with the onset of winter. Juveniles appear to show some resident behavior. Adults occur in shelf waters over muddy and sandy bottoms to 70 m but mainly off sandy beaches, where it is most abundant in the surf zone but does occur along the edges of reefs down to 30 m. Juveniles are mainly found in the surf zone along sandy beaches. Adults eat benthic molluscs, crustaceans, polychaetes (bristle worms), squid and small fish. The juvenile\u2019s diet is thought to be similar to that of adults. Giant Guitarfish are commonly caught by shore anglers in KZN and forms an important component of the competitive shore fishery where most fish are released. Also taken in shark nets along the KZN coast but most 150 (74%) are released alive. They comprise a small percentage (1.6%) of the bycatch taken by inshore prawn trawls off the Thukela Banks during summer. However, due to an extended closed trawl season implemented between Aug-Feb each year and diminished inshore prawn catches, the impact of the prawn trawl fishery on these has greatly diminished. Although this species faces fewer threats in SA, catches are seasonal occurring from October to May peaking in austral summer and it is possible that animals may also move to MOZ, where they are being increasingly targeted. Since the flesh and particularly the fins of Giant Guitarfish are highly sought after in Asian fish markets and the fact that the life history of this species makes it vulnerable to overexploitation. This is especially since they are targeted freely and often illegally by foreign longliners across a large proportion of its home range. A risk assessment showed a 65.1% decline in abundance over a period of three generation lengths, which indicates that the sampled population of R. djiddensis in South Africa should be classified as Endangered according to the IUCN Red List using criterion A2b.", "biology": "Reproductive style: Ovoviviparous, producing four young ~60 cm TL at birth. Breeding/spawning season: Dec-Feb (summer) in northern KZN. Breeding/spawning locality: Little known but thought to breed in shallow waters off sandy beaches in northern KZN and MOZ. Age at maturity: Based on the approximate length of males and females at first maturity the corresponding age would be about 1-2 years and 2-3 years for males and females rrespectively,but ages need verification. Length at maturity: Observed length at first maturity for males and females in KZN was 156-177 cm TL respectively. Maximum recorded age: Based on the maximum length (280 cm TL) recorded in SASAA angling records, the corresponding maximum age would be approximately 12-13 years but ageing needs verification. Maximum recorded weight: 123.9 kg (SASAA2), however aAlso reported to be 127.4 kg. Maximum recorded length:  280 cm TL (SASAA) but has also been reported to be 310 cm TL.", "citation": "CG Attwood, BQ Mann In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, Long-term catch trends and risk assessment of the Critically Endangered white-spotted wedgefish (Rhynchobatus djiddensis) from South Africa by Ryan Daly, Denham Parker, Geremy Cliff, Gareth L. Jordaan, Nkabi Nomfundo, Rhett H. Bennett, Bruce Q. Mann"}',
  '[{"measure": "TL", "reference": "Visboekie", "coefficient": 5.22e-06, "exponent": 3.0141, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "kg"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Acroteriobatus leucospilus',
  'Greyspot Guitarfish',
  'Gryskol Sandkruiper',
  'Guitarfish Greyspot',
  ARRAY['Greyspot Sandshark'],
  'Rhinobatidae',
  'Guitarfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  1,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Decreasing, Endangered',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Greyspot Sandshark", "appearance": "This species is distinguished by the following set of characters: dorsal surface smooth, no prominent thorns or tubercles, except for slightly enlarged granular denticles partially around orbital rims, and rather regularly distributed along midline from nape to near first dorsal-fin origin, none between dorsal fins and upper caudal fin; snout semi-translucent with elongated bluish spots giving stripe-nosed appearance, numerous small bluish spots covering the snout, pectoral, pelvic, dorsal, and caudal fins but not the central disc, on a sandy brown background with darker brown spots of varying sizes covering the disc, tail, fin bases, and fins, and sometimes giving the caudal peduncle a striped appearance, the outer edges of pectoral- and pelvic-fin margins blue, while lateral tail folds white or striped blue and brown and ventral surface white.", "about": "The Greyspot Guitarfish is a medium-sized coastal ray that occurs in the Western Indian Ocean off the coasts of Madagascar and East Africa from the central Transkei, Eastern Cape, South Africa to Tanzania and Zanzibar in shallow subtidal areas to a depth of 100 m. It feeds on bivalves, gastropods, shrimps, crabs and small bony fishes. Research is required on life history, abundance, and threats. Species-level monitoring should be undertaken.", "biology": "It is ovoviviparous (internal fertilization and the young are born alive) with embryos feeding initially on yolk, then receiving additional nourishment from the mother by indirect absorption of uterine fluid enriched with mucus, fat or protein through specialised structures do not feed off the mother. The young are born as miniature adults, free-swimming and feeding. Males and females mature at about 56 cm TL. Females bear 2 to 4 young with a birth size about 25 cm TL. Max length: 120 cmTL.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
  '[{"measure": "TL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.0221, "exponent": 2.56, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Acroteriobatus annulatus',
  'Lesser Guitarfish',
  'Kleiner Sandkruiper',
  'Guitarfish Lesser',
  ARRAY['Sandshark','Lesser Sandshark','Sandfis','Lesser Guitar-shark'],
  'Rhinobatidae',
  'Guitarfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  1,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Decreasing, Vunerable',
  'Stock status: Unknown - Fishing pressure: Unknown',
  '{"other_names": "Sandshark, Lesser Sandshark, Sandfis, Lesser Guitar-shark", "appearance": "This is a small guitarfish with a triangular, almost translucent snout and rounded pectoral fins. Tan to dark brown in colour with brown spots (KwaZulu-Natal) or white rings with brown centres (rest of South Africa).", "about": "Lesser Guitarfish are endemic to SA and are found from southern Angola to KZN in depths of 1-118 m. In SA they were previously thought to extend northwards up the west coast into NAM, but this may be as a result of misidentification with the Bluntnose Guitarfish (Acroteriobatus blochii). There is thus a possibility of two separate stocks, one in southern Angola to NAM and one along the south-eastern seaboard of SA. The latter population appears to have different colour variants with those in KZN having simple dark spots, while those in the EC and WC have brown spots ringed with white. Lesser Guitarfish are common in the surf-zone along sandy beaches during summer, but not in winter. It is possible that they move offshore into deeper water where they are taken as bycatch by inshore trawlers. A long shore movement is also possible. Adults inhabit sandy habitat - from the shallowest surf to inshore trawl grounds at depths of up to 73 m but have been recorded at a depth of 118 m off Sodwana. Juveniles utilise sandy surf-zones as a nursery. Adult\u2019s diet includes benthic invertebrates such as small crustaceans, sand mussels and polychaete worms. The juvenile\u2019s diet is unknown. Shore anglers catch this species mostly as bycatch, although they are sometimes targeted in catch and release angling competitions. They are also caught as a bycatch in the beach seine fishery in False Bay, but most are returned alive. Approximately 18 mt is taken annually as bycatch in the inshore trawl grounds, most of which is discarded.", "biology": "Reproductive style: Aplacental viviparity (embryos develop inside eggs that are retained within the mother''s body until they are ready to hatch) giving birth to 2-10 pups. Breeding/spawning season: Pupping season is from Mar-Apr. Breeding/spawning locality: Shallow inshore waters off sandy beaches throughout range. Age at maturity: Combined sexes: 3 years. Length at maturity: Males: 580 mm TL; Females: 615-650 mm TL. Maximum recorded age: 7 years. Maximum recorded weight: 9.1 kg (SASAA). Maximum recorded length: 1150 mm TL.", "citation": "CG Attwood, BQ Mann In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, ORI Fish Fact Sheet"}',
  '[{"measure": "TL", "reference": "Visboekie", "coefficient": 1.08e-06, "exponent": 3.18, "formula_type": "power-mm", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Rhinobatos holcorhynchus',
  'Slender Guitarfish',
  'Slank Sandkruiper',
  'Guitarfish Slender',
  ARRAY['Slender Sandshark'],
  'Rhinobatidae',
  'Guitarfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  1,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Decreasing, Data Deficient',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Slender Sandshark", "appearance": "A guitarfish with a narrow, sharply pointed snout and a narrow pectoral disc; nasal flaps extend only to the inner nostril edges. Colouration: Plain olive-green above, without spots; prominent black blotch on underside of snout.", "about": "The Slender Guitarfish is a small demersal shark-like ray that inhabits continental shelf waters in the Western Indian Ocean from KwaZulu-Natal, South Africa to Kenya at depths of 75-350 m. It may also be present in Madagascar. It inhabits the continental shelf at depths of 75-350 m. Further research is needed on distribution, life history, population size and trends, and threats. Population monitoring is needed. Guitarfish are among the most threatened elasmobranch families globally and are susceptible to rapid population declines. Given the high value of fins and meat of guitarfish, and the associated increase in targeting of guitarfish in the Western Indian Ocean and other areas, and there is the potential for a rise in capture and trade of the Slender Guitarfish.", "biology": "Like other guitarfishes, it exhibits ovoviparity (aplacental viviparity), with embryos feeding initially on yolk, then receiving additional nourishment from the mother by indirect absorption of uterine fluid enriched with mucus, fat or protein through specialised structures. Max length: 127 cm TL.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Chelidonichthys lastoviza',
  'African Gurnard',
  'Afrikaanse Knorhaan',
  'Gurnard African',
  ARRAY['Streaked Gurnard'],
  'Triglidae',
  'Gurnards, Searobins',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Streaked Gurnard", "meristics": "1st Dorsal spines: 9-11; 2nd Dorsal soft rays: 14-17; Anal spines: 0; Anal soft rays: 14-17.", "appearance": "The African Gurnard has a large triangular head with a steep forehead. Uniquely amongst gurnards, the body is covered with clear oblique ridges of skin that originate at the lateral line. The lateral line scales are enlarged and armed with small spines. It has two dorsal fins. The caudal fin is truncated. The first dorsal fin has a large dark blotch. The breast may or may not have scales, but the belly is scaled. The African Gurnard is red above and pale below with dark spots on the head and back. The moderately large grey pectoral fins have large dark blue and red bands or spots.", "about": "The African Gurnard is distributed in the Eastern Atlantic: Norway continuously south around Cape of Good Hope to Mozambique. This demersal species is found in open areas over gravel and sand from the coast down to a depth of about 150 m but usually 40 m. It feeds on crustaceans.", "biology": "Length at maturity: 15.0 cm. Max length: 40.0 cm TL; Common length: 15.0 cm TL. Max reported age: 18 years.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Specises, Wikipedia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Chelidonichthys kumu',
  'Bluefin Gurnard',
  'Blouvin  Knorhaan',
  'Gurnard Bluefin',
  ARRAY['Blue Gurnard','Pacific Red Gurnard','Rooster Gurnard'],
  'Triglidae',
  'Gurnards, Searobins',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Blue Gurnard, Pacific Red Gurnard, Rooster Gurnard", "meristics": "1st Dorsal spines: 9-10; 2nd Dorsal soft rays: 15-16; Anal spines: 0; Anal soft rays: 14-16.", "appearance": "The Bluefin Gurnard is a large bottom-dwelling fish known for its bright red body and large, colourful pectoral fins. The body\u2019s natural colour is splotchy pale brown to olive or brownish but becomes reddish to reddish-brown when stressed. It is paler or silvery-white below. The Bluefin Gurnard only has a few blue spots in a dark \"eyespot\". It has a boxy, bony head which is protected by backwards-facing spines along the front of the mostly smooth snout and around the eye as well as on the hind margin of the operculum and a row of prominent bony scales along the dorsal fin bases. The body tapers into a laterally elongated body. The inner surface of the pectoral fin is olive-green to greyish or purplish with scattered bluespots, surrounded by a bright blue edge; a large black blotch sometimes has white to bluish speckles near the finbase. There are 8-10 gill rakers and 70-80 scales on its lateral line, which is uninterrupted. The anal fin has 14-16 soft rays and no spines. The Bluefin Gurnard\u2019s large, fan-like pectoral fins are one of two pairs with 13-14 soft rays, and its pelvic fin has 5 soft rays and a single spine. The pectoral fins\u2019 first three rays are modified and separated from the rest of the fin. They are used as sensory organs, sometimes referred to as \u201cfingers\u201d, permitting it to probe the sea bottom to detect prey buried in the sand or the mud. These spectacular fins make the Bluefin Gurnard look like a butterfly of the sea; however, their role is not entirely known. They could be used to attract a mate or frighten off predators. These fan-like fins can also be used to give stability during swimming.", "about": "The Bluefin Gurnard is an Indo-Pacific searobin, distributed from Mozambique to Port Elizabeth in South Africa in the western Indian Ocean. In the Pacific, this species ranges from Vietnam, north to Japan and South Korea.  It is also reported in the Pacific from southern Australia and New Zealand and Hong Kong. Bluefin Gurnard is a benthic species that is found over open sand, mud and sandy shell bottoms, at a depth range of 1-200 m. It is a continental species associated with nutrient rich waters, and is often found in rivers, estuaries and transitional waters. The juveniles of this species may occur in bays.", "biology": "Length at maturity: 23.0 cm. Max length: 60.0 cm TL; Common length: 40.0 cm TL. Max published weight: 1.5 kg; Max reported age: 15 years.  Males are smaller than females at around 26 cm and 33 cm respectively.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia, Fishes of Australia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Chelidonichthys capensis',
  'Cape Gurnard',
  'Kaapse Knorhaan',
  'Gurnard Cape',
  NULL,
  'Triglidae',
  'Gurnards, Searobins',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Stable, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "1st Dorsal spines: 8-9; 2nd Dorsal soft rays: 15-17; Anal spines: 0; Anal soft rays: 14-16.", "appearance": "The head is comparatively high, and the eyes are on the top of the head. The large head shape is slightly rounded, not overly steep with strong bony ridges and spines. The snout is more elongated than the African Gurnard. The dorsal fin has no black blotch. The pectoral fins are mostly dark with blue and turquoise streaking; the inner pectoral fins have a wide margin of blue, with 3-4 bright blue spots or blotches. The Cape Gurnard lacks a blue edge on its pectoral fins found on the Bluefin Gurnard. The lower 3 white or pale pectoral rays are detached and finger-like. Scales on lateral line are not modified. The body is generally red -orange-brown.", "about": "90% of gurnards caught by anglers or spearfishermen are Cape Gurnards. Distribution: Southeast Atlantic and Western Indian Ocean: Cape Fria, Namibia south around the coast of South Africa to Maputo, Mozambique. It is found at depths ranging from 10-390 m.  It is a demersal species found on soft-bottom (sandy and muddy) substrates. The diet is mainly comprised of crustaceans, cephalopods and fishes.", "biology": "It is a pelagic spawner that exhibits a long laying reproductive period with spawning seasons ranging from November to January and from March to April with maximum spawning activity occurring in January and April. Males reach first sexual maturity at 37 cm total length at the age of 5 years, while females reach first sexual maturity at 35 cm total length at the age of 4 years.  The maximum recorded length for this species is 75 cm TL. Common length: 35.0 cm TL. The estimated maximum age for this species is 16 years at 67.5 cm TL for females.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia, Two Oceans Aquarium"}',
  '[{"measure": "TL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.00933, "exponent": 3.05, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Chelidonichthys queketti',
  'Lesser Gurnard',
  'Kleiner Knorhaan',
  'Gurnard Lesser',
  ARRAY['Spiny Gurnard','Longfin Gurnard','Cape Red Gurnard'],
  'Triglidae',
  'Gurnards, Searobins',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Stable, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Spiny Gurnard, Longfin Gurnard, Cape Red Gurnard", "meristics": "1st Dorsal spines: 9; 2nd Dorsal soft rays: 18-19; Anal spines: 0; Anal soft rays: 17-18.", "appearance": "There are 10 or 11 finrays within the pectoral fin membrane and three fin rays which are free of the membrane. There is a large spine on the anterior part of the preorbital and smaller spines behind that which may be covered in skin. The overall colour and pattern is mottled, red and brown. The bony head with strong spines and upper body are mottled reddish while the lower third of the body and the anal fin are white. The soft trayed dorsal fin and the caudal fin are reddish brown with no dark blotch on the 1st spinous dorsal fin. The very long pectoral fins are blackish with a pinkish lower third, and the pelvic fins are pinkish red with white margins.", "about": "This species is found from Cape Town, South Africa to Maputo Bay, Mozambique. It has been collected at depths ranging of 0-500 m, but is commonly found at depths of 50-150 m. While this species appears rare throughout most of its range, it is considered to be the most common and abundant species of Triglidae in Agulhas Bank and is commonly found inhabiting various sediment types. It is a fast growing and long-lived species. The diet comprises of amphipods, brachyurans, polychaetes, echinoderms, crustaceans, and molluscs and fishes.", "biology": "It spawns throughout the year with peak spawning activity occurring in the spring and late summer months. The age and size at first sexual maturity for females is 1 year at 19.5 cm. The maximum recorded length is 35 cm TL. The maximum recorded age is 7 years.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Merluccius capensis',
  'Shallow-water Hake',
  'Vlakwater Stokvis',
  'Hake Shallow-water',
  ARRAY['Shallow-water Cape Hake','Cape Hake','Stockfish','Stockvis','Hake'],
  'Merlucciidae',
  'Hakes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  5,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  'Stock Status: Abundant; Fishing pressure: Optimal',
  '{"other_names": "Shallow-water Cape Hake, Cape Hake, Stockfish, Stockvis, Hake", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 1; Dorsal soft rays: 47-54; Anal spines: 0; Anal soft rays: 37-41.", "appearance": "It is a long, lean fish with a large head, light brownish above and white or silvery below. Tips of pectoral fins usually reach origin of anal fin; posterior margin of caudal fin truncate or slightly concave.  Scales are small.", "about": "Shallow-water Hake are distributed in the south-eastern Atlantic and western Indian Oceans on the continental shelf from southern Angola on the west coast to KZN on the east coast. They constitute the main stock in waters shallower than 300 m. The stock structure is uncertain. Differences in body and eye colour between NAM and SA populations suggest different stocks north and south of the environmental barrier off Luderitz. This proposed stock structure is supported by some, but not all genetic studies. They are residents where individuals move to deeper water with age so that the mean size increases with increasing water depth.  Adults utilize a wide range of habitats from rough, rocky bottom to sandy substrates. The main population resides in waters shallower than 300 m, but adults have also been recorded at 508 m during DAFF research cruises. The juvenile\u2019s habitat is similar to adults, but in shallower waters. Zero-year fish are often found in oxygen-deficient inshore waters e.g. off the Orange River. This could indicate a high tolerance to low oxygen conditions providing protection from predators. Adults are mainly piscivorous but may also eat cephalopods (octopus and squid) and crustacea. Most common prey is deep-water hake. Early juveniles prey on euphausids (shrimp-like planktonic marine crustaceans) and amphipods (crustaceans with no carapace) but become more piscivorous with increasing size; largely piscivorous diet from about 25 cm TL. The two hake species are the main target species of the offshore demersal trawl fishery, but about 70-80% of the hake catch is deep-water hake. Although Shallow-water Hake is less important to this sector, it nonetheless takes more than any other fishing sector. About 8% of the global hake TAC is allocated to the inshore hake trawl sector. Shallow-water Hake is the main target species of this fishery and is the dominant species in the catch; however the total catch is less than that taken by the offshore trawl sector. 10% of the global Hake TAC is allocated to hake longline plus hake handline. The majority of the hake catch taken by the hake longline and hake handline sectors is shallo-water hake, however many of the hake longline and hake handline right holders are not currently active due to the current economic climate. Some hake (mainly shallow-water hake) is taken as unavoidable bycatch in the midwater trawl fishery for horse mackerel. Current management is fully effective, and no further improvements are required.", "biology": "In common with other hake species this is a batch spawner.  Breeding/spawning season: All year, but with peak spawning in Sep-Oct. Breeding/spawning locality: Widespread on the continental shelf, but with some localised seasonal aggregations. Age at maturity: Males: 2.2 years; Females: 4.1 years; (SA west coast). Length at maturity: Males: 29.5 cm TL; Females: 46.8 cm TL; (SA west coast). Maximum recorded age: Female: 13 years; (SA south coast). This fish was a 99 cm TL female but larger fish that have not been aged have been recorded, so maximum age is likely to be greater than 13 years. Maximum recorded weight: Female: 12 kg (SA west coast). This was the heaviest fish recorded in DAFF research surveys. Maximum recorded length: 108 cm TL (SA west coast). This was the longest fish recorded in DAFF research surveys but fish of up to 115 cm TL have been seen on commercial vessels.", "citation": "RW Leslie, D Durholtz In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, FishBase, Wikipedia, FAO"}',
  '[{"measure": "TL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.0057, "exponent": 3.073, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Euleptorhamphus viridis',
  'Ribbon Halfbeak',
  'Lint Halfbek',
  'Halfbeak Ribbon',
  ARRAY['Longfin Garfish'],
  'Hemiramphidae',
  'Halfbeaks',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Not Evaluated',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Longfin Garfish", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 0; Dorsal soft rays: 21-25; Anal spines: 0; Anal soft rays: 20-25.", "appearance": "Body very elongate; lower jaw is very prolonged; upper jaw short, triangular, and scaly; teeth present on vomer and tongue; back iridescent blue green; belly silvery; pectoral fins long; fins transparent. It is an extremely slender garfish with compressed ribbon-like body, and an extremely long lower jaw that may be as long as half the standard length.", "about": "Ribbon Halfbeak are found in the Indo-Pacific: Red Sea and East Africa to Hawaii, Tonga, north to southern Japan, and south to Australia, New Zealand and Kermadec Islands. Eastern Pacific: southern California, USA to Ecuador, including the Galapagos Island. They are usually oceanic, but they enter large open bays. They can fly above the water surface to evade large carnivorous fish and dolphins. They lack the usual large pelvic tail wings to fly but solve this problem by rotating their rear body by 90\u00b0 and use their wide dorsal and anal fins as a horizontal tail wing.", "biology": "Max length: 53.0 cm TL; Common length: 30.0 cm SL", "citation": "FishBase, Fishes of Australia, The Society for Experimental Biology"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Hemiramphus far',
  'Spotted Halfbeak',
  'Gevlekde Halfbek',
  'Halfbeak Spotted',
  NULL,
  'Hemiramphidae',
  'Halfbeaks',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Not Evaluated',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 0; Dorsal soft rays: 12-15; Anal spines: 0; Anal soft rays: 10-12.", "appearance": "The Spotted Halfbeak has a laterally compressed body which is elongate oval in cross-section and has a very long, beak-like lower jaw with a short upper jaw which is triangular and lacks scales; there is no preorbital ridge. It has short pectoral fins which do not extend past the nasal fossa when they are folded forwards. There are 3-9, normally 4-6, dark vertical bars on the sides and the back is bluish in colour dorsally with silvery sides. The caudal fin is asymmetrical with the lower lobe being longer than the upper lobe. The dorsal fin and the anal fin are located towards the tail and are dark in colour.", "about": "It has an Indo-Pacific distribution and has invaded the eastern Mediterranean through the Suez Canal.", "biology": "It breeds in estuaries, and in the more temperate parts of its distribution in the spring and summer. The eggs are attached to vegetation by sticky threads and once the larvae hatch they are planktonic.", "citation": "FishBase, Wikipedia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Hyporhamphus affinis',
  'Tropical Halfbeak',
  'Tropiese Halfbek',
  'Halfbeak Tropical',
  NULL,
  'Hemiramphidae',
  'Halfbeaks',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Not Evaluated',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 0; Dorsal soft rays: 14-17; Anal spines: 0; Anal soft rays: 15-19.", "appearance": "The Tropical Halfbeak has a blue back with a silvery stripe on side, silvery white underparts and a blue caudal fin while the other fins are colourless. The distal half of the underside of the elongated lower jaw is bright red. There is a well developed anterior lobe on the dorsal fin and the caudal fin has a slightly longer lower lobe than the upper. The upper jaw is scaled; the pre-orbital region is much longer than the upper jaw.", "about": "It has an Indo-Pacific distribution from the Red Sea and coasts of eastern Africa east through the Indian Ocean islands to Western Australia, New Guinea, Philippines, and islands of Oceania and has been recorded in the Mediterranean Sea which it reached through the Suez Canal. It is found mainly at depths between 0 -6 m in proximity to coral reefs and islands. It occurs in schools and feeds mainly on zooplankton, as well as small fish and detritus.", "biology": "The eggs are covered with adhesive filaments and are attached to floating and benthic objects. They grow to a maximum length of 38 cm SL.", "citation": "FishBase,Wikipedia"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.00068, "exponent": 3.575, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Cirrhitus pinnulatus',
  'Marbled Hawkfish',
  'Marmer Valkvis',
  'Hawkfish Marbled',
  ARRAY['Stocky Hawkfish'],
  'Cirrhitidae',
  'Hawkfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Stocky Hawkfish", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 10; Dorsal soft rays: 11; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 6.", "appearance": "The overall colour of the Marbled Hawkfish is brown with white blotches and irregular reddish-brown spots on the body. It has a continuous dorsal fin. There is a deep incision between spiny and soft rayed parts of the fin and a tassel of cirri near tip of each spine. The head is marked with sinuous reddish-orange lines and spots. There is a dark saddleilike blotch on the dorsal part of the caudal peduncle. The head has a short, blunt snout and a large mouth which extends back as far as the rear edge of the eye which has a low bony ridge above it. The mouth has two types of teeth, an outer row of canines and an inner row of villiform teeth. There are also teeth on the centre and sides of the roof of the mouth. They have a fringe of cirri on the posterior margin of the anterior nostril. The upper margin of the preopercle has fine serrations.", "about": "Indo-Pacific: Red Sea and East Africa to the Marquesan Islands and Mangar\u00e9va, north to southern Japan and the Hawaiian Islands, south to the Kermadec and Rapa Islands.It occurs at depths between 1-23 m but is typically found at depths of less than 15 m.This species is found in exposed areas such as the surge zone on the seaward sides of reefs and along rocky coastlines. It inhabits reef fronts and rocky shorelines exposed to moderate to strong surge to depths of about 3 m. It lives in the benthic zone and feeds primarily on crabs, but also takes other crustaceans, small fishes, sea urchins or brittle stars.", "biology": "They are pelagic spawners; the pair ascend into the water column to release their gametes. They are likely to be protogynous hermaphrodites, but further study is needed to confirm this. Max length: 30.0 cm TL; Common length: 23.0 cm TL.", "citation": "FishBase,Wikipedia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Chirocentrus dorab',
  'Wolf Herring',
  'Wolfharing',
  'Herring Wolf',
  ARRAY['Dorab Wolf-herring','Wolf-herring','Silky'],
  'Chirocentridae',
  'Wolfherrings',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Dorab Wolf-herring, Wolf-herring, Silky", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 0; Dorsal soft rays: 16-19; Anal spines: 0; Anal soft rays: 29-36.", "appearance": "The slightly shorter pectoral fin, 11-13% of standard length, and the black marking of the upper part of the dorsal fin are the only satisfactory characters separating this species from Chirocentrus nudus, Whitefin Wolfherring; there is also some black on the anterior part of the anal fin.", "about": "Wolf Herring is widespread in the Indo-Pacific, specifically in the Persian Gulf, the Red Sea, Durban, South Africa, the Philippines, Japan, and northern Australia. The species is known from the shore to a depth of about 120 m. It is a pelagic, inshore fish found in the warmer waters of the tropical Indo-Pacific. It is a voracious predator of small schooling fishes, e.g. herrings and anchovies and crustaceans.", "biology": "The species is known to spawn year-round in Indian waters. It reaches sexual maturity in both males and females once it is over 10 months old, with the females at an average of 49.2 cm TL and the males being at an average of 48.6 cm TL. Max length: 100.0 cm SL (male); 36.6 cm SL (female); Common length: 60.0 cm TL.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.052, "exponent": 2.391, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Bodianus perditio',
  'Goldsaddle Hogfish',
  'Goudsaal Varkvis',
  'Hogfish Goldsaddle',
  ARRAY['Golden-spot Hogfish'],
  'Labridae',
  'Wrasses',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  'Abundant',
  '{"other_names": "Golden-spot Hogfish", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 12; Dorsal soft rays: 10; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 11.", "appearance": "The lateral line is smoothly curved, following the dorsal contour of body. The caudal fin of juveniles is truncate but in adults double emarginate with long pointed lobes. The central white bar of the juvenile diminishes to an oval yellow spot above the lateral line. The caudal peduncle of the juvenile has a central white patch surrounded by a dark bar extending full width.", "about": "This species occurs in three widely disjuct areas of distribution in the Indo-Pacific: from the Natal coast of South Africa to the Mascarene Islands. Also found in eastern Australia, and northern Madagascar. Also found in the Northern Hemisphere from Taiwan and southern Japan. It is a subtropical, non-migratory species; depth range 10-120 m. It inhabits the vicinity of coral and rocky deep offshore reefs, often over sand or rubble in deeper water but juveniles may occur as shallow as 9 m. It feeds mainly on benthic invertebrates such as molluscs and crustaceans. This species is an excellent food fish.", "biology": "It is oviparous with distinct pairing during breeding. Max length: 80.0 cm SL. Max. published weight: 31.20 kg.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "formula_type": "log-linear", "coefficient": -11.34317988, "exponent": 3.148749421}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Bodianus bilunulatus',
  'Saddleback Hogfish',
  'Saalrug Varkvis',
  'Hogfish Saddleback',
  ARRAY['Blackspot Wrasse','Crescent-banded Hogfish','Hawaiian Hogfish','Table Boss','Tuxedo Hogfish','Tarry Hogfish','Saddleback Wrasse'],
  'Labridae',
  'Wrasses',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Blackspot Wrasse, Crescent-banded Hogfish, Hawaiian Hogfish, Table Boss, Tuxedo Hogfish, Tarry Hogfish, Saddleback Wrasse", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 12; Dorsal soft rays: 10; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 12.", "appearance": "Young easily identified by the unusual colouration. Adults normally have an oval shaped black saddle near the tail, but it may become indistinct in large males.", "about": "This species is found in the Indo-Pacific from Somalia to Durban, South Africa to the Abrolhos Islands, Western Australia. In the Western Pacific, it is found from Wakayama, Japan to Bali, Indonesia and New Caledonia. Adults occur on deep reef slopes rich with invertebrates such as sponges and seawhips, but young adults are occasionally seen much shallower. They are usually solitary in coral and rocky reefs and feed mainly on benthic, hard-shelled, invertebrates such as mollusks and crustaceans.", "biology": "They are protogynous (hermaphrodite; female reproductive organs come to maturity before the male) and oviparous (egg laying) displaying distinct pairing during breeding. Max length: 55.0 cm TL; Max. published weight: 1.8 kg.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
  '[{"measure": "TL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.0146, "exponent": 3.0, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Congiopodus torvus',
  'Smooth Horsefish',
  'Gladde Perdvis',
  'Horsefish Smooth',
  NULL,
  'Congiopodidae',
  'Mail-cheeked fishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Least Concern, Unknown',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 20-21; Dorsal soft rays: 13-15; Anal spines: 0; Anal soft rays: 7-8.", "appearance": "The Smooth Horsefish is a compressed fish with a long continuous dorsal fin that is very high over the head.  There is a projecting snout with a small, terminal mouth and a single nostril at each side. Adults are smooth skinned, but the skin of juveniles is covered with small rough bumps. It is usually light brown with irregular darker brown markings in young; adults are darker brown.", "about": "The Smooth Horsefish is distributed from Namibia to Kwazulu-Natal, South Africa. The Smooth Horsefish is a subtropical demersal species that has a depth range of 10-300 m and inhabits soft bottoms of the continental shelf.  This species feeds on benthic crustaceans.", "biology": "Max length: 76.0 cm TL; Common length: 30.0 cm TL.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Pachymetopon blochii',
  'Hottentot',
  'Hottentot',
  'Hottentot',
  ARRAY['Cape Bream','Kaapse Brasem','Hotnot Vis','Hotnot','Kaapse Galjoen','Black Bream'],
  'Sparidae',
  'Seabreams, Porgies',
  22,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  'Stock Status: Abundant; Fishing Pressure: Light',
  '{"other_names": "Hotnot Vis, Hotnot, Kaapse Galjoen, Black Bream, Cape Bream, Cape Seabream", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 10; Dorsal soft rays: 11-12; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 10.", "appearance": "The Hottentot is a small bronze-grey seabream, lighter below, with small dark fins. The small mouth contains five rows of incisors in both upper and lower jaw, but no molars which allow it to fulfill its omnivorous diet. About the Species Hottentot are endemic and occur from Angola to Port Alfred but are most abundant between Port Nolloth and Cape Agulhas. They are residents where adults inhabit rocky reefs and kelp beds to depths of 55 m while juveniles occupying shallow water in kelp beds. Adults are omnivorous and feed mainly on algae but also take amphipods (beach fleas, sand hoppers, etc), crabs, shrimp, worms, hydroids (small predators related to jellyfish), molluscs, sea urchins, redbait and occasionally fish. Juveniles are also omnivorous, especially partial to small crustaceans.  Hottentot are an important component of the artisanal linefishery in the WC, especially when higher-value species such as Cape Snoek and Cape Yellowtail are not available. They are also important to recreational shore anglers and ski-boat fishers in the WC. Also caught as a bycatch of the gill-net fishery on the West Coast and occasionally speared.", "biology": "Reproductive style: Gonochorist (separate sexes). Breeding/spawning season: Throughout the year with peaks in winter and summer. Breeding/spawning locality: Throughout its distribution range. Age at maturity: Females: 4 years; WC. Combined sexes: 5 years. Length at maturity: Females: 202 mm FL; WC; Combined sexes: 220 mm FL; WC.  Maximum recorded age: 21 years; WC. Maximum recorded weight: 2.67 kg; (SAUFF). Maximum recorded length: 54 cm TL.", "citation": "SE Kerwath, H Winker In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, Wikipedia and Two Oceans Aquarium. For more information: http://speciesstatus.sanbi.org/assessment/last-assessment/1035/"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "Visboekie", "coefficient": 3.31e-05, "exponent": 2.9467, "formula_type": "power-mm", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Pachymetopon aeneum',
  'Blue Hottentot',
  'Blou Hottentot',
  'Hottentot Blue',
  ARRAY['Blue Cape Bream','Blou Kaapse Brasem','Blue Bream','Bluefish','Copper Bream','Butterfish'],
  'Sparidae',
  'Seabreams, Porgies',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  5,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Increasing, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": " Blue Bream, Bluefish, Copper Bream", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 10-11; Dorsal soft rays: 11-13; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 10. The head is cobalt blue, the body blue-streaked bronzy-yellow. Blue Hottentot are often confused with Bronze Bream. They can be distinguished by checking their teeth; Blue Hottentot have more teeth.", "about": "Blue Hottentot are endemic to SA occurring from False Bay to Sodwana but are more abundant in southern KZN and the EC. Movement patterns are unknown but seasonal component of linefish catches in southern KZN, and northern Transkei suggests the possibility of a northward spawning migration. Adults inhabit high-profile inshore and offshore reefs 20-80 m while juveniles prefer shallow subtidal reefs (10-20 m). Adults are benthic carnivores feeding mainly on hydrozoans (solitary and colonial polyps and jellyfishes), tunicates (sea squirts and salps), octocorals (sea pens) and mysids (small, shrimp-like crustaceans). The juvenile\u2019s diet is similar to adults\u2019. Blue Hottentot are an important component of the offshore commercial and recreational ski-boat fisheries in the EC and KZN and are occasionally taken by skilled spearfishers capable of diving in deeper water. Blue Hottentot appears to become an increasingly important component of linefish catches, particularly in the EC however this corresponds to a decreasing trend in mean size in the Port Alfred commercial and recreational linefishery.", "biology": "Reproductive style: Protogynous hermaphrodite with sex change from female to male occurring between 200-300 mm FL. Breeding/spawning season: Reproductively active fish caught throughout the year but mainly in summer (Sep-Mar) in the EC and spring (Aug-Nov) in KZN. Breeding/spawning locality: Prime spawning area appears to be off the former Transkei and southern KZN although ripe fish have been recorded in southern parts of the EC and in northern KZN. Age at maturity: Females: 4.5-6 years; EC. Length at maturity: Females: 200-250 mm FL; EC. Maximum recorded age: 12 years; male; EC. Maximum recorded weight: 4.75 kg; KZN; (SADSAA). Maximum recorded length: 60 cm TL.", "citation": "BQ Mann, ST Fennessy In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180 and Two Oceans Aquarium. For more information: http://speciesstatus.sanbi.org/assessment/last-assessment/1029/"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "Visboekie", "coefficient": 1e-05, "exponent": 3.149, "formula_type": "power-mm", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Helicolenus dactylopterus',
  'Jacopever',
  'Jakopewer',
  'Jacopever',
  NULL,
  'Sebastidae',
  'Rockfishes and thornyheads',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 12; Dorsal soft rays: 12-13; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 5.", "appearance": "The back and sides are red and the belly is pink, with 5 to 6 dark bands below anterior, middle and posterior dorsal spines: below the soft dorsal rays and at the base of the caudal fin; a Y-shaped dark bar between the soft dorsal and anal fin; and usually a dark blotch on the posterior part of the spinous dorsal fin. As with other species of scorpionfish, the spines of the blackbelly rosefish contain toxic venom and have reportedly caused injuries to humans. However, there has been little research on the venom produced by this species", "about": "Jacopever is widely distributed in the Western Atlantic Ocean: Nova Scotia, Canada to Venezuela. Eastern Atlantic: Iceland and Norway to the Mediterranean and the Gulf of Guinea, including Madeira, the Azores, and the Canary Islands. It is also found from Walvis Bay, Namibia to KZN, South Africa. Adults are found in soft bottom areas of the continental shelf and upper slope. They feed on both benthic and pelagic organisms (crustaceans, fishes, cephalopods, and echinoderms). This is a bathydemersal species that can be found in soft bottom areas of the continental shelf and upper slope, usually between 150-600 m.", "biology": "The reproductive mode is a zygoparous form of oviparity, intermediate between oviparity and viviparity. Fertilization is internal. The females can store sperm within their ovaries that allows them to spawn multiple batches of embryos, which are enclosed within a gelatinous matrix secreted into the ovarian cavity. Larvae and juveniles are pelagic. Length at maturity:  32.0 cm. Max length: 50.0 cm TL; Common length: 25.0 cm TL; Max. published weight: 1.6 kg. Max. reported age: 43 years.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Sebastes capensis',
  'False Jacopever',
  'Vals Jakopewer',
  'Jacopever False',
  ARRAY['Cape Redfish'],
  'Sebastidae',
  'Rockfishesand thornyheads',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Cape Redfish", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 13-14; Dorsal soft rays: 13-14; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 6.", "appearance": "Body shape: fusiform, is a robust fish, with a large head. The general colour of this fish is reddish or brown, and there are five or six pale spots on its back.", "about": "The False Jocopever is a marine, demersal subtropical species that is known from Tristan da Cunha, Gaugh Island and the tip of South Africa where it is locally abundant. It is a bottom-dwelling marine fish that inhabits shallow and rocky areas. The depth range for this species is 20-275 m. It is an economically important species to artisanal fishermen as well as being part of the bycatch in lobster potting in Tristan da Cunha and in fishing surveys off South Africa. It is an economically important species to artisanal fisheries in some parts of its range. It feeds on small benthic invertebrates and mysids. There are no species-specific conservation measures currently in place, though parts of its range do overlap with marine protected areas.", "biology": "It is a viviparous species, retaining the eggs internally until they hatch. In the fiords of southern Chile, the young larvae occupy the channels where copepod eggs are plentiful while larger larvae move onto shelf areas where the salinity is higher and larger copepod prey is more abundant. Max length: 37.0 cm TL; Common length: 30.0 cm TL.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Aphareus furca',
  'Blue Smalltooth Jobfish',
  'Blou Kleintand Jobvis',
  'Jobfish Blue Smalltooth',
  NULL,
  'Lutjanidae',
  'Snappers',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 10; Dorsal soft rays: 10-11; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 8.", "appearance": "This fish contains long filaments at the tips of its tail fin. Dorsal fin is continuous. It is silvery purpleish brown to bronzeish blue-gray on back and silvery blue below with dark margins on the preopercle and opercle. It has whitish to yellowish-brown fins fins. Males may be identified by yellow present on the head. Small juveniles have a yellow tail.", "about": "The Blue Smalltooth Jobfish is widespread in the Indo-Pacific: East Africa to the Hawaiian Islands, north to southern Japan, and south to Australia. It is often curious and approachable. It is typically found at depths between 1-120 m but has been observed to be deeper than 300 m. It is a pelagic and benthopelagic species that inhabits inshore coral and rocky reef areas, rocky bottoms and in clear water lagoons. This species occurs singly or in small groups and is primarily piscivorous but also eats crustaceans.", "biology": "Max length: 70.0 cm TL; Common length: 25.0 cm; Max. published weight: 906 g.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia, fishIDER, Fishes of Australia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Aprion virescens',
  'Green Jobfish',
  'Groen Jobvis',
  'Jobfish Green',
  ARRAY['Kaakap','Kaalkop'],
  'Lutjanidae',
  'Snappers',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": " Kaakap, Kaalkop", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 10; Dorsal soft rays: 11; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 8.", "appearance": "Body elongate and robust; very distinct horizontal groove on snout ventral to nostrils; teeth in both jaws in bands, with strong canines anteriorly; teeth on roof of mouth in chevron- or crescent-shaped patch; last soft ray of both dorsal and anal fins well produced, longer than next to last ray to form a short filament ; caudal fin forked; short pectoral fins, less than 1/2 length of head, about equal to length of snout; membranes of dorsal and anal fins without scales. Colour of body dark green, bluish, or greenish blue to grey or greyish blue along upper body with pale belly; may have dark spots along base of dorsal fin.", "about": "Green Jobfish are found in the Indo-Pacific: East Africa to the Hawaiian Islands, north to southern Japan, south to Australia. In southern Africa they are common north of St Lucia but also observed as far south as Pondoland in the Eastern Cape. Their movement patterns are unknown in SA. Adults inhabit inshore reef areas, from the surface down to 100 m depth. Juveniles have been recorded far from land, borne along by ocean currents.  Adults are diurnal (daytime) predators feeding mainly on fish, but also on crustaceans and cephalopods (octopus and squid). Consumption of planktonic and mid-water prey suggests pelagic foraging. The juvenile\u2019s diet is unknown. They are commonly targeted species by recreational ski-boat anglers and spearfishermen, particularly in northern KZN and MOZ. Green Jobfish are considered to be a \u201csemi-pelagic gamefish species\u201d and thus legally targeted by recreational ski-boat anglers and spearfishers in controlled areas of the St Lucia and Maputaland MPAs. However, low numbers, primarily of small individuals occurring in these areas in contrast to nearby no-take areas suggest that this species is vulnerable to exploitation due to residency.", "biology": "Reproductive mode is gonochoristic (separate sexes) and fertilization is external via egg scattering in open water or near the substratum. Spawning has been recorded from Jan-May and in Nov in east African waters. Age at 50% maturity: 3-4 years; SA; 4-5 years; Hawaii; disparities in size at sexual maturity between areas may reflect differences in resource utilization and growth rate. Length at 50% maturity: 700-750 mm TL; SA. Another study found that maturity was reached at 410-465 mm SL in males and females respectively in Kenyan waters.  Maximum recorded age: 16 years; Great Barrier Reef. Maximum recorded weight: 20.2 kg; Japan. SA spearfishing record: 16.8 kg; KZN. Maximum recorded length: 112 cm TL; Female; Seychelles.", "citation": "C Floros, JQ Maggs In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180 and State of Queensland (Department of Agriculture and Fisheries), FishBase"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.0294, "exponent": 2.76, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Aphareus rutilans',
  'Red Smalltooth Jobfish',
  'Rooi Kleintand Jobvis',
  'Jobfish Red Smalltooth',
  ARRAY['Rooi Kleintand-job','Kleintand-Jobvis','Red Smalltooth Job','Rusty Jobfish','Small Tooth Jobfish','SilvergillJobfish'],
  'Lutjanidae',
  'Snappers',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Rooi Kleintand-job, Kleintand-Jobvis, Red Smalltooth Job, Rusty Jobfish, Small Tooth Jobfish, Silvergill Jobfish", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 10; Dorsal soft rays: 10-11; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 8.", "appearance": "It has an elongated, compressed and fusiform body. It has a lower jaw which projects beyond the upper and the mouth extends to the centreline of the eye. It has a flat area between the eyes. The jaws are quilted with thin bands of small teeth. There are no teeth on the roof of the mouth. The rearmost rays in both the dorsal and anal fins are elongated. The caudal fin is deeply forked or lunate in shape. The overall colour is blueish grey to mauve or reddish with the dorsal, pectoral and caudal fins being yellowish to reddish. The lips of the upper jaw are dark.", "about": "The Red Smalltooth Jobfish is widespread in the Indo-Pacific from Hawaii to East Africa (Port Alfred, South Africa) and from the Ryukyu and Ogasawara islands southward to Australia.  It is found in depths of between 10 m and 330 m. This is a pelagic and benthopelagic species, inhabiting reefs and rocky bottom areas to depths of at least 330 m; however, it is most commonly found between 100-250 m, but has been reported as shallow as 10-15 m. It feeds on fish, squids and crustaceans.", "biology": "The age of maturity is 3.8 years.  The maximum age expressed as mean age in published literature is 18 years. Max length: 110 cm; Common length: 79.0 cm; Max. published weight: 11.3 kg.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Pristipomoides filamentosus',
  'Rosy Jobfish',
  'Dagbreek Jobvis',
  'Jobfish Rosy',
  ARRAY['Crimson Jobfish','Crimson Snapper','Hawaiian Pink Snapper'],
  'Lutjanidae',
  'Snappers',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Crimson Jobfish, Crimson Snapper, Hawaiian Pink Snapper", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 10; Dorsal soft rays: 11; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 8.", "appearance": "This species is distinguished by the following characters: body elongate, laterally compressed; jaws about equal or lower jaw protruding slightly; premaxillae protrusible. maxilla extending to vertical through about anterior margin of pupil; upper and lower jaws both with an outer row of conical to small canine teeth and an inner band of villiform teeth, the caniniform teeth at anterior ends of jaws are not appreciably enlarged; teeth on vomer triangular patch, maxilla without scales or longitudinal ridges; interorbital region flattened. Last soft ray of both dorsal and anal fins well produced, longer than next to last ray; caudal fin forked; pectoral fins long, about equal to or somewhat shorter than head length; membranes of dorsal and anal fins without scales. Colour variable, ranging from brownish to lavender or reddish purple; snout and interorbital space with narrow yellow lines and blue spots often persisting as dark spots when preserved; dorsal and caudal fins light blue or lavender with reddish orange margins.", "about": "Rosy jobfish   are distributed in the Indo-Pacific: East Africa to Hawaii and Tahiti, north to southern Japan, and south to eastern Australia and Lord Howe Island. In southern Africa they extend from MOZ south to Algoa Bay. Movement patterns are unknown but are considered more pelagic than most other lutjanid species, however, it is likely to be fairly resident as with most other lutjanids. Adults occur down to at least 270 m, although they are sometimes found in shallower water when conditions are favourable. They are associated with reefs, sandy and muddy bottom, but often seen or caught in midwater. Juveniles are reported to occur over relatively flat, soft bottom (>60 m deep) in Hawaii.  Adults eat small fish, mantis shrimps, mysids, squid, crabs, amphipods (crustaceans with no carapace), ascidians (sea squirts) and pelagic items such as salps (free-swimming marine invertebrates) and urochordates (animals with dorsal nerve cords and notochords). The juvenile\u2019s diet is unknown. They are taken in fair numbers during summer by recreational and commercial ski-boat fishers along the Zululand coast in northern KZN, also on Protea Banks on the KZN lower south coast. Their preference for deep water and generally being of small size makes it of limited importance in the spearfishery. A large proportion of the SA population is either protected in MPAs or cannot be targeted because of its preference for deeper water on the shelf-edge where strong surface currents often make linefishing difficult.", "biology": "Rosy Jobfish   are gonochoristic (separate sexes), batch and broadcast spawners whose season is unknown in SA but occurs in summer months from Oct-Apr, peaking in Feb in Seychelles from the Mah\u00e9 Plateau. Age at maturity: Unknown. Length at maturity: Combined sexes: 36-52 cm FL; Seychelles. Maximum recorded age: 18 years. Maximum recorded weight: 8.2 kg, 7 kg (SAUFF). Maximum recorded length: 89 cm TL.", "citation": "JQ Maggs, BQ Mann In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, FishBase"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.025, "exponent": 2.93, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Pristipomoides multidens',
  'Striped Jobfish',
  'Gestreepte Jobvis',
  'Jobfish Striped',
  ARRAY['Goldbanded Jobfish'],
  'Lutjanidae',
  'Snappers',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Goldbanded Jobfish", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 10; Dorsal soft rays: 11; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 8.", "appearance": "It has an elongated, robust body. The space between the eyes is flat and it has a slightly protruding lower jaw. In both upper and lower jaws there is an outer row of conical and canine-like teeth, the front 2-3 pairs of canines are enlarged, and an inner band of bristle-like teeth. The vomerine teeth are arranged in a triangular patch and there are no teeth on the tongue. The bases of both the dorsal and anal fins lack scales and the last soft ray of each of these fins is extended into a short filament. The pectoral fins are long extending as far as the anus. The caudal fin is forked. The overall colour is yellowish to pale pink marked with 6 interrupted, golden stripes on the flanks; the sides of the snout and the cheek have a pair of blue-edged golden stripes while the crown has a series of yellow chevrons pointing towards the snout. The dorsal fin has yellowish stripes or lines of spots.", "about": "This species is widely distributed in the Indo-Pacific: East Africa and Red Sea to Samoa, and southern Japan southward to Australia. It is a deepwater, demersal species inhabiting tropical and sub-tropical waters. It is a schooling fish and lives in areas of hard, rocky and uneven sea floor near steep drop-offs. This species feeds on fishes, shrimps, crabs, lobsters, stomatopods, squids, gastropods and urochordates (sea squirts).", "biology": "This species is a serial spawner. Similar studies suggest that this species is a multiple spawner. During spawning eggs are scattered in open water. Fecundity ranges from 296,000 to 2,800,000 eggs per year. The age of maturity is 3.2 years.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Gymnocrotaphus curvidens',
  'John Brown',
  'Janbruin',
  'John Brown',
  ARRAY['Blue-eye JB'],
  'Sparidae',
  'Seabreams, Porgies',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  5,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Blue-eye JB", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 10; Dorsal soft rays: 11-12; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 9 - 10.", "appearance": "The body is rather plump and deep.  The dorsal profile of the head is concave in front of the eyes and just above the eyes too. There is a band of curved incisor-like teeth in each jaw with a band of smaller conical teeth inside this and the very small molar-like teeth inside those. Eyes are deep blue; the brown of live specimens fade quickly, leaving orange lines along the scale rows; sometimes with narrow dark crossbars.", "about": "John Brown is a South African endemic from the Cape to Durban that inhabits shallow reef areas. This species is primarily caught by spearfishers and shore anglers and rarely taken by recreational ski-boat anglers. It is a highly resident species that primarily inhabits shallow reef areas, but adults are known to occur to depths of up to 50-80 m.  Juveniles are fairly common in intertidal gullies while adults are found on subtidal reefs normally down to about 25 m. This species feeds on redbait, seaweed, bryzoans (simple, small, aquatic invertebrate animals living in colonies), polychaete worms and small crustaceans.", "biology": "Max length: 50.0 cm TL. Maximum weight recorded is 3.7 kg.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "Student Thesis", "coefficient": 1e-05, "exponent": 3.1843, "formula_type": "power-mm", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

