  'Kersfees Papegaaivis',
  'Parrotfish Christmas',
  ARRAY['Starry-eye Parrotfish','Carolines Parrotfish'],
  'Scaridae',
  'Parrotfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Starry-eye Parrotfish, Caroline\u2019s Parrotfish", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 9; Dorsal soft rays: 10; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 9.", "appearance": "The species changes its appearance greatly during the transition to adulthood. Juveniles of the species are typically a mottled orangish-brown, with some pink shading. Adult males of the species are shades of blue or green or grayish brown with scales with fine whitish markings, shading to brownish red ventrally, and have 3 short dull reddish to pink lines radiating from their eyes. Adult females are mottled brown, and their eyes bulge out slightly. The head is paler ventrally. The dorsal spines are flexible. Caudal fin rounded in juveniles, double emarginate with slightly prolonged lobes in large males. Skin black around anus. Lateral line interrupted. The pelvic fins are brownish red with blotches or spots. The eyes have a dull reddish-brown iris. Its jaws consist of pebble-like teeth fused into a beak for eating seaweed, but in juveniles the teeth are not yet fully fused and are visible on the outside of the dental plate.", "about": "This species is the widest ranging member of the genus and occurs from the east coast of Africa to the Galapagos and Revillagigedos islands. To the north it extends to the Ryukyu and Ogasawara Islands and south to the Great Barrier Reef and New Caledonia. This species inhabits subtidal reef flats, and lagoon and seaward reefs to a depth range of 1-71 m but commonly at 27 m. It is found in coral, rubble, seagrass and weedy areas. It occurs singly or in small groups. It feeds on a variety of benthic encrusting algae and seagrasses.", "biology": "This species is a protogynous hermaphrodite and may be monandric where only a few females turn into males. Max length: 54.0 cm TL.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Scarus rubroviolaceus',
  'Ember Parrotfish',
  'Kool Papegaaivis',
  'Parrotfish Ember',
  NULL,
  'Scaridae',
  'Parrotfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 9; Dorsal soft rays: 10; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 9.", "appearance": "The species is sexually dimorphic, with the males possessing a bright, greenish-blue colour while the females are a duller brown. Colour of male with distinct bicolour pattern, brownish to dark green on head and anterior body and lighter green on posterior portion; female reddish brown to grey with small black spots and irregular black lines and white flakes on body. The caudal fin is slightly emarginated in female, lunate with prolonged lobes in terminal male.", "about": "It is one of the most abundant and widespread of all parrotfishes. Indo-Pacific: East Africa south to Durban, South Africa and east to the Tuamoto Islands, north to the Ryukyu and Hawaiian Islands, south to Shark Bay, Western Australia and the southern Great Barrier Reef. Eastern Pacific: Gulf of California to the Galapagos Islands. This species is a large parrotfish that may form dense schools (300-400 individuals). It is also found solitary or in pairs. It occurs on non-reefal rocky areas and on coral reefs. It extends to deeper parts of the reef to 36 m. It is a component of subsistence fisheries and is heavily fished in parts of its range. There have been indications of localized population declines in Indonesia, Philippines and the Solomon Islands.", "biology": "This fast-growing species is oviparous displaying distinct pairing during breeding and a protogynous hermaphrodite. Sex change occurs at 37.4 cm TL and 13 years of age. Max length: 70.0 cm TL; Max reported age: 20 years.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Scarus scaber',
  'Fivesaddle Parrotfish',
  'Vyfsaal Papegaaivis',
  'Parrotfish Fivesaddle',
  NULL,
  'Scaridae',
  'Parrotfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 9; Dorsal soft rays: 10; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 9.", "appearance": "There is marked sexual dimorphism. The males are dark blue to steel grey or olive like. There is a teal-coloured horizontal band from the tip of the muzzle to the operculum passing under the eye. The upper body is blue and grades into blueish yellow or green. The females have a steel grey upper body and white lower body that grade into pinkish beige. Scales are grey. There is a dark grey to black horizontal bar that extends from the tip of the muzzle to the operculum, crossing the eye.", "about": "It is native to Indian Ocean: East Africa south to KZN, South Africa; also, around islands of the western Indian Ocean. It inhabits sheltered water environments of shallow lagoon reefs, in areas with dense coral cover in a depth range of 1-20 m. Individuals in the initial phase form groups. It feeds on algae by incessant grazing in coral reefs.", "biology": "Max length: 37.0 cm TL; Max published weight: 0.9 kg.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia, heritagebelombre.com"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Bolbometopon muricatum',
  'Humphead Parrotfish',
  'Ramkop Papegaaivis',
  'Parrotfish Humphead',
  ARRAY['Green Humphead Parrotfish'],
  'Scaridae',
  'Parrotfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Decreasing, Vulnerable',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Green Humphead Parrotfish", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 9; Dorsal soft rays: 10; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 9.", "appearance": "Unlike wrasses, it has a vertical head profile, and unlike other parrotfishes, it is uniformly covered with scales except for the leading edge of the head, which is often light green to pink. Primary phase colouration is a dull gray with scattered white spots, gradually becoming uniformly dark green. This species does not display sex-associated patterns of colour change. The adult develops a bulbous forehead, and the teeth plates are exposed, being only partly covered by lips.", "about": "The Humphead Parrotfish is the largest species of parrotfish. It is found on reefs in the Indian and Pacific Oceans, from the Red Sea in the west to Samoa in the east, and from the Yaeyama Islands in the north to the Great Barrier Reef, Australia, in the south. This species is gregarious and usually occurs in small aggregations, but group size can be quite large on seaward and clear outer lagoon reefs, exceeding 75 individuals. Newly settled juveniles are found in branching coral habitats (primarily Acropora) in sheltered lagoons. Small juveniles (<50 mm) are often associated with Damselfish. Larger juvenile Humphead Parrotfish are found in lagoons, often in seagrass beds, and the adults are found in clear outer lagoons and seaward reefs up to a depth of 30 m. They feed on benthic algae and live corals. Adult Humphead Parrotfish may ram its head against corals to facilitate feeding. Each adult fish ingests over five tons of structural reef carbonates per year, contributing significantly to the bioerosion of reefs. The fish sleeps among corals, in caves and shipwrecks at night, usually in large groups.", "biology": "The fish are oviparous with distinct pairing during breeding and spawn pelagically near the outer reef slope or near promontories, gutters, or channel mouths during a lunar cycle, usually spawning just prior to the new moon and make use of spawning aggregation sites. Max length: 130 cm TL; Common length: 70.0 cm SL; Max. published weight: 46.0 kg", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia,"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Leptoscarus vaigiensis',
  'Marbled Parrotfish',
  'Marmer Papegaaivis',
  'Parrotfish Marbled',
  NULL,
  'Scaridae',
  'Parrotfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 9; Dorsal soft rays: 10; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 9.", "appearance": "Unlike other parrotfishes, males and females look very similar. The marbled parrotfish, when fresh is olive brown to greenish with darker mottling on the back fading to yellow or greenish ventrally. The males are marked with a pale longitudinal strip along their flanks, and the head, body, dorsal fin and anal fin are marked with small blue spots. The females are mottled brown and white. On the head the females have broad bands which radiate from the eyes.", "about": "This species is widely distributed throughout the Indo-Pacific region and is also found in the southeastern Atlantic Ocean, False Bay, South Africa. It is found in both the Southern and Northern Hemispheres, but rare or absent near the Equator. It is also relatively common in most of its range. The Marbled Parrotfish lives in sheltered bays, harbours and lagoons among seagrass beds and algal-covered reefs. It normally occurs in small groups. It ranges in depth from 0-15 m. Their diet consists of sea grass and algae.", "biology": "Uniquely among parrotfish, females never change sex to males. They are gonochristic. Spawning occurs in shallow water over flat seagrass beds on the ebbing tide. Max length: 35.0 cm TL.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Calotomus spinidens',
  'Spinytooth Parrotfish',
  'Stekeltand Papegaaivis',
  'Parrotfish Spinytooth',
  NULL,
  'Scaridae',
  'Parrotfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 9; Dorsal soft rays: 10; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 9.", "appearance": "General body colour when fresh is greenish brown with scales finely flecked with pale; shade of white ventrally (belly sometimes dull rose or yellowish). Across the chin, 2 irregular dull reddish bars interspaced by white or yellow; upper opercular margin with a diffused dark spot. It has glassy pectorals with a yellowish flush, pelvic fins glassy except for numerous small white spots and some reddish blotches. Dorsal spines are flexible. Area circumscribed by pectoral fin unspotted. Lateral line is interrupted.", "about": "This species is found from Kenya to at least Delagoa Bay in Mozambique, and east to the Marshall and Tonga Islands. This species is found in coastal bays and deep lagoons. It inhabits seagrass beds or dense beds of algae. It feeds on these or the associated epiphytes (organisms that grow on the surface of a plant). This species is well-camouflaged and easily overlooked.", "biology": "Length at maturity: 10.5 cm. Max length: 30.0 cm TL.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Sardinops sagax',
  'Pilchard',
  'Suid Afrikaanse Pelser',
  'Pilchard',
  ARRAY['Sardine','Sardien','Sardyn'],
  'Clupeidae',
  'Herrings, Sardines, Pilchards, Shads',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  'Stock Status: Optimal; Fishing Pressure: Optimal',
  '{"other_names": "Sardine, Sardien, Sardyn. Note: In South Africa it is referred to as S. ocellatus or S. sagax ocellatus by some authors.", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 0; Dorsal soft rays: 13-21; Anal spines: 0; Anal soft rays: 12-23.", "appearance": "Body cylindrical and elongate; ventral part of operculum with clear cut bony striae radiating downwards; belly rounded with ventral scutes; back blue green; flanks white, with 1-3 series of dark spots along the middle. The radiating bony striae (a linear mark, slight ridge, or groove on a surface, often one of a number of similar parallel features) on the operculum distinguish this species from all other clupeids (herrings, shads, sardines) in the area.", "about": "It is found in the Indo-Pacific and East Pacific oceans. Sardinops sagax has a wide anti-tropical distribution (exists at comparable latitudes across the equator but not in the tropics). This species occurs in coastal waters to a depth of about 200 m. This is a marine, pelagic and migratory species forming large shoals that may spread over several kilometers. With each year of life, migration becomes farther. It was previously thought that east coast Sardines represent a separate stock component that mixes with Sardines resident on the south coast during summer but then separates from them during winter to travel toward their east coast spawning grounds. Using genomic data, it was found that east coast Sardines were not unique, but clustered with west coast sardines, and were distinct from those on the south coast. This new finding suggests that Sardines participating in the run must be migrants that originate from the cool-temperate Atlantic, and are not actually well adapted to the warmer, subtropical conditions on the east coast. Observed variations in the geographical distribution of Sardine stocks associated with changes in population size are thought to be closely influenced by prevailing winds, currents and local phytoplankton and zooplankton concentrations. The KwaZulu-Natal Sardine run is a mass migration of South Africa\u2019s commercially most important small pelagic fish from warm-temperate waters on the south coast to subtropical waters on the east coast. It is one of Earth\u2019s most spectacular marine migrations and is both ecologically and economically important. It is a highly commercial species throughout much of its range and supports some of the largest global fisheries. This species primarily feeds on zooplankton, mostly small crustaceans (i.e., copepods, ostracods, euphausiids and mysids), but also feeds on mollusc larvae and phytoplankton.", "biology": "It is oviparous, with pelagic eggs, and pelagic larvae. Research on related species suggests that they may spawn a number of times a year. Batch fecundities range from about 10,000 eggs in 13 cm long females to about 45,000 eggs in females of about 18 cm. Length at maturity: 15 cm. Max length: 39.5 cm SL; Common length: 20.0 cm SL; Max published weight: 486.0g. Max reported age: 25 years.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, DEFF 2020 - Status of the South African marine fishery resources, 2020; Oceans and Coasts Annual Science Report 2021,DFFE."}',
  '[{"measure": "TL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.0093, "exponent": 3.06, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Parastromateus niger',
  'Black Pomfret',
  'Swart Pomfret',
  'Pomfret Black',
  NULL,
  'Carangidae',
  'Kingfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Decreasing, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 2 - 6; Dorsal soft rays: 41-46; Anal spines: 2; Anal soft rays: 35-40.", "appearance": "It is a deep-bodied fish and strongly compressed with dorsal and ventral profiles being equally convex. Lateral line ends in weakly-developed scutes on the caudal peduncle. Pelvic fins are lost in individuals over 9 cm. This species has small dark grey scales which cover the entirety of the body. Colour is brown above, silvery-white below. The anterior parts of the dorsal and anal fins bluish gray. The other fins yellowish. The fins contain dark edges, and young specimens have dark vertical bars with long black jugular pelvic fins.", "about": "Black Pomfret is a species of carangid native to reefs of the Indian Ocean and western Pacific Ocean: East Africa to southern Japan and Australia. Adults inhabit coastal areas with muddy substrates within the depths of 15-40 m but the depth range can be up to 105 m. Found near the bottom during daytime and near the surface at night. They also enter estuaries. They normally form large schools. It swims on its side near the surface. It feeds on zooplankton and is an excellent food fish.", "biology": "Length at maturity range: 22-24 cm. Max length: 75.0 cm TL; Common length: 30.0 cm TL. Further studies need to be done in order to determine the maximum age of the black pomfret as well as the reproduction.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "formula_type": "log-linear", "coefficient": -10.76624012, "exponent": 3.011996031}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Trachinotus botla',
  'Largespot Pompano',
  'Grootkol Pompano',
  'Pompano Largespot',
  ARRAY['Wave Garrick','Large Spotted Pompano','Largespotted Dart'],
  'Carangidae',
  'Kingfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  5,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Stable, Least Concern',
  'Under exploited, >50% of pristine',
  '{"other_names": "Wave Garrick, Large Spotted Pompano, Largespotted Dart", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 7; Dorsal soft rays: 22-24; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 19-22.", "appearance": "Bluish black above, silvery below; 1-5 large spots on or near LL (absent in specimens less than 15 cm, number of spots increasing with age); caudal, 2nd dorsal and anal fins dusky to blue-black, the lobes usually darker.", "about": "Largespot Pompano are widespread Indo-Pacific species from Algoa Bay northwards to Kenya, also Madagascar, Sri Lanka as well as eastern and western Australia. In southern Africa they are mainly found along the KZN north coast and northwards into MOZ, seldom seen south of Port St Johns along the former Transkei coast. The ORI Tagging Project reveals this species appears to be a surf-zone resident however, some fish have undertaken movements in excess of 100 km. Adults inhabit shallow coastal waters, often preferring the rough surf zone along sandy beaches and rocky ledges while juveniles are found in the shallowest part of the surf zone where they are at times stranded by receding waves. They are intolerant of fresh or turbid water. They are important in the recreational shore fishery in northern KZN and MOZ and are often targeted by light-tackle anglers. Catch rates are higher north of St Lucia.", "biology": "Largespot Pompano are gonochoristic (separate sexes) with a protracted breeding/spawning season throughout the summer probably in northern KZN beginning when the reach the age of 2-3 years when males reach a length of 25.3 cm FL and females, 24.2 cm FL. The maximum recorded age is 6 years, the maximum recorded weight is 2,5 kg and the maximum recorded length is 60 cm TL.", "citation": "D Parker, AJ Booth In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, FishBase"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 2e-05, "exponent": 2.96, "formula_type": "power-mm", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Trachinotus baillonii',
  'Smallspot Pompano',
  'Kleinkol Pompano',
  'Pompano Smallspot',
  ARRAY['Pamphlet','Moonfish','Small Spotted Dart'],
  'Carangidae',
  'Kingfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Pamphlet, Moonfish, Small Spotted Dart", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 7; Dorsal soft rays: 20-24; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 20-24.", "appearance": "The body colour varies from silvery blue to grey above, with some small black spots on the flanks. The number of these spots increases with age. This fish is silvery white below. It has large, strong fins, a forked tail, and a narrow base.", "about": "This species is widespread in the Indo-Pacific, from the Red Sea and coast of East Africa to the Gambier Islands and southern Japan. The Smallspotted Pompano is a reef-associated species. It can be found in lagoons and seaward reefs, usually in schools near the surface of waters and in surge zones along sandy beaches in a depth range of 0-3 m. They move in schools at the edge of the surf near the reef, usually in pairs or small groups. They feed on small fishes but mainly on crustaceans and worms. It is relatively common throughout its range and is of only minor commercial importance. They are occasionally taken by trolling and line fishing.", "biology": "Max length: 60.0 cm TL; Common length: 35.0 cm TL; Max published weight: 1.5 kg.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.01288, "exponent": 2.96, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Trachinotus blochii',
  'Snubnose Pompano',
  'Stompneus Pompano',
  'Pompano Snubnose',
  NULL,
  'Carangidae',
  'Kingfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 7; Dorsal soft rays: 18-20; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 16-18.", "appearance": "Lateral line is only slightly irregular, weakly convex above pectoral fin, becoming straight posteriorly. Colour: head and body generally silvery, blue grey above, paler below, large adults some time with most of body golden orange especially snout and lower half of body. Second dorsal fin dark, lobe of fin dusky orange; anal fin dusky dirty orange, lobe with a brownish anterior margin; caudal fin dark to dirty orange with leading edges of fin darkest. Pelvic fins white to dirty orange, pectoral fins dark. Juveniles are silvery with pale fins except lobes of median fins and anterior half of pelvic fins brownish to dirty orange.", "about": "The Snubnose Pompano occurs in coastal waters throughout the Indo-West Pacific. It is relatively common throughout its range and is of minor commercial importance. Juveniles inhabit sandy shorelines and shallow sandy or muddy bays near river mouths while adults move out in schools to clear seaward coral and rock reefs. Juveniles are in small schools, while adults are usually solitary. The diet consists of crabs, sand mollusks and other hard-shelled invertebrates and worms.", "biology": "Max length: 110 cm FL; Common length: 40.0 cm TL; Max published weight: 3.4 kg.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "formula_type": "log-linear", "coefficient": -7.522987605, "exponent": 2.252003003}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Trachinotus africanus',
  'Southern Pompano',
  'Suidelike Pompano',
  'Pompano Southern',
  ARRAY['African Pompano'],
  'Carangidae',
  'Kingfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  5,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "African Pompano", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 7; Dorsal soft rays: 21-23; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 19-21.", "appearance": "It is a very deep bodied fish, silver in colour with blue fins with yellow margins. The fish has a blunt nose and does not have large spots.", "about": "Southern Pompano are distributed in the Indian Ocean spanning the Gulf of Aden and Oman, MOZ and SA across to western Indonesia suggesting that a distributional gap along most of African east coast may reflect a collecting artifact indicated that the gap may be real and merely reflect limited availability of preferred habitat. In southern Africa this fish occurs locally between Knysna (WC) and Delagoa Bay in southern MOZ but is seldom caught south of KZN. The ORI Tagging Project indicates that adults may be fairly wide ranging. A southward migration into KZN waters occurs during the summer months. Adults are found in the surf-zone along sandy beaches but usually in close association with nearshore reefs or rocky outcrops. Juveniles make use of sheltered bays as nursery areas, particularly along Durban''s beachfront and may sometimes enter estuaries. Adults feed primarily rock mussels, also sand mussels, sand dollars, crabs and mole crabs. Southern Pompano are caught primarily by shore anglers and spearfishers along the KZN and MOZ coast. Juveniles are sometimes taken in great numbers as a bycatch in the beach seine fishery in Durban. It is propably the most popular recreational species, and highly targeted, especially in KZN.", "biology": "Little is known about the biology and ecology of Southern Pompano but thought to be gonochoristic (separate sexes) with a breeding/spawning season in spring in northern and southern when they reach the age of 2-3 years however their length at maturity is unknown. Some individuals are known to live for over 10 years. The maximum recorded weight is >25 kg and the maximum recorded length is 92 cm FL.", "citation": "JQ Maggs, BQ Mann In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, FishBase, Wikipedia"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 3.64e-05, "exponent": 2.887, "formula_type": "power-mm", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
