  'Not Evaluated',
  'Protected',
  '{"other_names": "", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 9-12; Dorsal soft rays: 12; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 7-9.", "appearance": "The body is covered with small, firmly attached scales which run up the base of the dorsal and anal fin. It has a large mouth and eyes. The preoperculum has a spiny margin while the operculum has a thick bony strut running horizontally at eye level which terminates in a spine.  It has a rounded anal fin and rounded pectoral fins, and a large, powerful, square-shaped tail. Its lower jaw protrudes from the top, and their very large eyes are adapted for hunting and inhabiting low-light conditions. The back and flanks are dark brown or grey in colour with darker spots and blotches fading to yellowish or silvery white on the belly. The fins are blackish brown. Juveniles are generally blue in colour.", "about": "H\u0101puku Wreckfish is a subtropical deepwater species and found around southern Australia, southern South America, South Africa, Tristan da Cunha and New Zealand at depths between 30-854 m but generally prefers waters deeper than 50 m. It occurs in seamounts and generally over rough ground. Juveniles are thought to be pelagic, switching to demersal when they are about 50 cm in length. They are usually found living in cracks, caverns, or caves when found in shallow waters. They are voracious predators, feeding on a large barracouta and pilchards and other fish species, invertebrates and crustaceans, squid and cuttlefish and octopuses. The fish has an overlapping range with the Atlantic Wreckfish, its closest known relative. It is taken by droplining down to 400 m and is sometimes seen in the trawled catch. H\u0101puku Wreckfish is a commercially valuable species and is valued as a food fish. It has become an important species for New Zealand''s aquaculture sector.", "biology": "H\u0101puku Wreckfish are primary gonochorists and are a large, slow growing, long-lived species. They reach sexual maturity between 10 and 13 years and have lifespans up to 60 years. They can grow as large as 100 kg but are usually found around the 25 kg mark. They have an average size of 80-100 cm but can grow up to 180 cm in length.", "citation": "FishBase, The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, Wikipedia"}',
  NULL
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Seriola lalandi',
  'Cape Yellowtail',
  'Kaapse Geelstert',
  'Yellowtail Cape',
  ARRAY['Yellowtail','Giant Yellowtail','Reuse Geelstert','Southern Yellowtail','Amberjack','Yellowtail Amberjack','Yellowtail Kingfish','King Yellowtail','Northern Kingfish','Amberfish','Halfkoort'],
  'Carangidae',
  'Kingfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Stable, Least Concern',
  'Stock status: Optimal;  Fishing Pressure: Optimal',
  '{"other_names": "Yellowtail, Giant Yellowtail, Reuse Geelstert, Southern Yellowtail, Amberjack, Yellowtail Amberjack, Yellowtail Kingfish, King Yellowtail, Northern Kingfish, Amberfish, Halfkoort", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 5 - 6; Dorsal soft rays: 33-35; Anal spines: 2-3; Anal soft rays: 20-21.", "appearance": "The Cape Yellowtail is the only jack without scutella on the caudal peduncle. Dark blue dorsally and almost white ventrally; with a well-defined line of demarcation between the two colours. Juvenile Yellowtail are rarely seen, as they are often found far from land associated with floating debris or weeds which provide camouflage. Juveniles are yellow with black bands. This colouration fades as the fish ages, and by about 30 cm in length, the fish has assumed its adult colouration.", "about": "Cape Yellowtail is a circumglobal nomadic species confined to warm temperate shelf waters and seamounts and oceanic Islands. In SA it occurs from Namibia to northern KZN but is mostly concentrated in shelf waters of the Western Cape. The fish aggregate and move between offshore reefs such as Alphard, 72-, 45- and 12-Mile banks in the Agulhas region and Bellows Rock, the Anvil, Rocky Bank around the Cape but can also be found along the West Coast between Dassen Island and Hondeklip Bay, as well as offshore areas such as Tripp and Vema Seamounts. Adults move up the east coast to KZN during winter following the sardines. They are epipelagic (occupy the uppermost layer of the world''s oceans which is bathed in sunlight during the daytime) with larger fish occurring to depths of 40 m. Juvenile shoals are associated with flotsam. Adults pray on pelagic baitfish species such as sardines, mackerels, anchovies as well as squid and crustaceans. Cape Yellowtail are amongst the top four species landed by the traditional commercial linefishery in terms of total reported catch, often only surpassed by Cape Snoek. They are also targeted by artisanal beach seine fishers, recreational ski-boat fishers, shore anglers and spearfishers. Purse-seining for Cape Yellowtail has been prohibited since 1982. Cape Yellowtail is optimally exploited according to fisheries scientists and latest stock assessments.", "biology": "Cape Yellowtail are gonochoristic (separate sexes) with a breeding/spawning season lasting from Nov-Feb occurring between Southern KZN to Cape Point when 2-3 years old when males attain a length of 470 mm FL and females, 834 mm FL. In Australia the maximum recorded age is 21 years but in SA this is only 11 years. The maximum recorded weight is 58,5 kg and the maximum recorded length is 143 cm FL.", "citation": "SE Kerwath, CG Wilke In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, FishBase, Wikipedia"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.0331, "exponent": 2.7566, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Seriola dumerili',
  'Greater Yellowtail',
  'Groot Geelstert',
  'Yellowtail Greater',
  ARRAY['Greater Amberjack'],
  'Carangidae',
  'Kingfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Unknown, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Greater Amberjack", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 8; Dorsal soft rays: 29-35; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 18-22.", "appearance": "The shape of the body is elongated and fusiform and it is of moderate depth and laterally compressed and has a covering of small cycloid scales. Anal fin is about 2/3 the length of the second dorsal fin. The body is brownish or bluish grey to olivaceous above, silvery white below; amber stripe on their head, extending from their nose to their first dorsal fin which becomes more defined when the fish is excited or feeding. Some fish may show a light yellow to reddish-brown stripe along the flanks. The fins are dusky. The second dorsal and anal fins have low anterior lobes. Juveniles have a yellow colour and five or six dark vertical bars along the sides with clear fins.", "about": "Greater Yellowtail are circumglobal, distributed in subtropical and tropical seas. In southern Africa they are found along the east African coast as far south as Algoa Bay.  They are migratory and oceanodromous. Adults inhabit deep reefs and deep offshore canyons or drop-offs, mainly from 18-72 m but recorded as deep as 360 m. Juveniles, small individuals, less than 3 kg, may be taken in shallow water less than 10 m. Smaller juveniles are associated with floating plants or debris in oceanic and offshore neritic waters (shallow part of the ocean above the drop-off of the continental shelf approx. 200 m deep) Adults primarily feed on mostly crab, small fishes found on reefs and squid. The juvenile\u2019s diet consists of plankton, including crustacean larvae and other small invertebrates. Predators include seabirds and larger fishes, such as Yellowfin Tuna. They are targeted primarily by recreational ski-boat fishermen using vertical jigging tackle on deep reefs and are occasionally caught by commercial ski-boat fishers. Although its preference for deeper water makes is difficult to target by spearfishers, small individuals may occasionally be taken by this sector.", "biology": "Greater Yellowtail are gonochoristic (separate sexes) and utilize external fertilization in the summer months. Eggs have been recorded offshore in depths >50 m off the KZN south coast. They mature at age 4 when males reach 113 cm SL and females, 109 cm SL. A female can release between 18 and 59 million eggs during a single spawning season. Females grow larger in size and live longer than males. The maximum recorded age is 15 years for a female (Gulf of Mexico) but can live to be 17 years old. The maximum recorded weight is 80.6 kg but are most commonly found to be up to 18 kg. The maximum recorded length is 188 cm TL.", "citation": "JQ Maggs, BQ Mann In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, FishBase, IGFA, Wikipedia"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.0423, "exponent": 2.747, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Seriola rivoliana',
  'Longfin Yellowtail',
  'Langvin Geelstert',
  'Yellowtail Longfin',
  ARRAY['Almaco Jack','Langvin-geelstert'],
  'Carangidae',
  'Kingfishes',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  10,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Stable, Least Concern',
  NULL,
  '{"other_names": "Almaco Jack, Langvin-geelstert", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 8; Dorsal soft rays: 27-33; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 18-22.", "appearance": "Front of dorsal fin and anal fin are high and elongated. Anal fin is about 2/3 the length of the second dorsal fin. This species is distinguished by the following characters: upper jaw posterior very broad, extends to level of middle of pupil; length of dorsal-fin lobe about 1.3 to 1.6 times longer than pectoral fins and 18 to 22% of fork length; caudal peduncle with dorsal and ventral grooves present; first pterygiophore of anal fin straight in specimens larger than about 10 cm fork length. Colour: dorsal brown or silvery blue-green to olivaceous, ventral paler or silvery with brassy or lavender reflections, with yellow midlateral stripe usually present, and an oblique, dark yellowish brown band from nape through eye to edge of upper lip, the nuchal bar often persistent in adults (may be absent); juveniles (2-18 cm fork length) with dark nuchal bar and 6 dark body bars, each with a light narrow irregular area through their centre vertically, that do not extend into the membranes of the second dorsal and anal fins, and a seventh bar at the end of caudal peduncle; fins dark or yellowish grey except pelvic fins, white ventrally.", "about": "Longfin Yellowtail are circumtropical, including Red Sea and Persian Gulf. Here in SA they occur from Knysna in the WC and northward along the east coast of Africa. Recent reports indicate their range may extend as far south as Arniston in the WC. Adults occur in oceanic waters and over coral and rocky reefs as well as outer-reef slopes and offshore banks between 30-160 m. Juveniles <20 cm occur below floating objects at sea. They are caught mainly by recreational ski-boat anglers using baits or artificial lures, especially vertical jigs; also targeted by spearfishers. Occasionally they are caught by commercial boat-based linefishers. Increasingly they are being used for mariculture internationally due to their fast growth rate in captivity.", "biology": "Longfin Yellowtail are gonochoristic (separate sexes) with a breeding/spawning season in spring in tropical areas at unknown age and length.  The maximum age is unknown. The maximum recorded weight is 59,9 kg and the maximum recorded length is 160 cm FL.", "citation": "JQ Maggs, BQ Mann In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, FishBase"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "FishBase", "coefficient": 0.0146, "exponent": 3.055, "formula_type": "power", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

INSERT INTO species (
  scientific_name, common_name, afrikaans_name, catalogue_name,
  other_names, family_scientific, family_common,
  minimum_size_cm, minimum_size_note, bag_limit, bag_limit_note,
  closed_season, iucn_status, sa_status, text_data, formulas
) VALUES (
  'Diplodus hottentotus',
  'Zebra',
  'Wildeperd',
  'Zebra',
  ARRAY['Bontrok','Bontdassie','Mbentsu'],
  'Sparidae',
  'Seabreams, Porgies',
  30,
  NULL,
  5,
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'Stable, Least Concern',
  'Over exploited, 25-40% of pristine',
  '{"other_names": "Bontrok, Bontdassie, Mbentsu Note: Zebra were previously described under the name Diplodus cervinus hottentotus, an endemic subspecies found along the eastern seaboard of southern Africa.", "meristics": "Dorsal spines: 11; Dorsal soft rays: 12-14; Anal spines: 3; Anal soft rays: 11.", "appearance": "Zebra has a deep, oval and compressed body. The upper jaw has 10 or 12 incisor-like teeth in the front of the upper jaw and 8 in the lower jaw. The background colour of the body is bright yellow with 5 wide vertical dark bars along the back and flanks, the snout is black and the gill cover is grey. The fins are grey too, except in juveniles which have a pink caudal fin with a black bar at its base. Juviniles are bright yellow between vertical crossbars. Zebras use their fleshy lips to grasp food and then move it into position for the cutting using their incisor teeth.", "about": "Zebra are endemic occurring from False Bay to southern MOZ. The species of Zebra found off southern Angola is believed to be a separate species. Tagging recapture data show it to be highly resident, the mean distance moved was 3 km. Juveniles have also been shown to be highly resident in rocky intertidal nursery areas. Adults can be found on rocky reefs from the surf-zone down to 60 m and more recently observed in canyons off Sodwana Bay at depths of 120 m. Juveniles inhabit shallow subtidal reefs, subtidal gullies, intertidal rock-pools and estuary mouths. Adults are benthic carnivores and specialize on polychaete worms and amphipods (crustaceans with no carapace) but also consume decapod crustaceans (crayfish, crabs, lobsters, prawns, and shrimp), ophiuroids (Starfish), echinoids (sea urchins) and gastropods (snails, whelks and slugs). Juveniles eat mainly amphipods and small polychaete worms but also feed on chironomid (fly) larvae and harpacticoid copepods (small free swimming marine shrimps). Zebra are caught primarily in the shore fishery where it is of moderate importance throughout its distribution but seldom caught in large numbers. Larger specimens are occasionally shot by spearfishers or caught by ski-boat fishers. Zebra is a slow growing, late maturing species susceptible to overexploitation. However, catches of this species appear to have been sustained due to various fisheries management interventions and the establishment of SA''s network of no-take MPAs.", "biology": "Reproductive style: Rudimentary hermaphrodite (functional gonochorist) (possessing both male and female potential prior to sexual maturation where no sex change occurs in mature individuals). Breeding/spawning season: Aug-Dec peaking in Oct in the EC. Breeding/spawning locality: Inshore reefs probably throughout distribution. Age at maturity: Combined sexes: 6 years. Length at maturity: Combined sexes: 280 mm FL. Maximum recorded length: 60 cm TL; Common length: 30.0 cm TL. Maximum recorded age: 33 years; male. Maximum recorded weight: 6.0 kg.", "citation": "BQ Mann, SW Dunlop In: Mann BQ. (Ed). Southern African Marine Linefish Species Profiles. Special Publication, Oceanographic Research Institute, Durban 9: 179-180, FishBase, Two Oceans Aquarium. Wikipedia For more information: http://speciesstatus.sanbi.org/assessment/last-assessment/1061/"}',
  '[{"measure": "FL", "reference": "MANN B.Q. and C.D. BUXTON", "coefficient": 1.27e-05, "exponent": 3.141, "formula_type": "power-mm", "result_unit": "g"}]'
);

